WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.500 --> 00:00:06.369
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:00:06.369 --> 00:00:08.410
SPEAKER: Thank you,
everyone, for taking the time

00:00:08.410 --> 00:00:12.340
to join us today, both in
person and on the livestream.

00:00:12.340 --> 00:00:15.370
I am so excited to
introduce you to Dr. Leigh

00:00:15.370 --> 00:00:18.820
Thompson from the Kellogg
School of Business.

00:00:18.820 --> 00:00:21.220
She has been a professor
there for many years

00:00:21.220 --> 00:00:23.740
and has done a tremendous
amount of research

00:00:23.740 --> 00:00:28.100
in the areas of negotiation,
collaboration, creativity,

00:00:28.100 --> 00:00:31.150
and teamwork, which
in our daily lives

00:00:31.150 --> 00:00:34.480
obviously are essential
to solving problems

00:00:34.480 --> 00:00:37.610
and to helping to move
the company forward.

00:00:37.610 --> 00:00:40.420
So when I heard that she
had a new book out that

00:00:40.420 --> 00:00:42.880
was focusing
specifically on helping

00:00:42.880 --> 00:00:44.710
teams and managers
solve problems

00:00:44.710 --> 00:00:46.666
in new and creative
ways, I absolutely

00:00:46.666 --> 00:00:48.290
wanted to have her
come and talk to us.

00:00:48.290 --> 00:00:51.430
So without further
ado, Leigh Thompson.

00:00:51.430 --> 00:00:54.450
LEIGH THOMPSON: Well,
good afternoon, everybody.

00:00:54.450 --> 00:00:56.580
So this is the
title of the book--

00:00:56.580 --> 00:00:58.170
"Stop Spending, Start Managing."

00:00:58.170 --> 00:01:02.520
And I want to give a head nod to
my hyper-talented collaborator,

00:01:02.520 --> 00:01:05.519
first author of the book--
this professor Tanya Menon

00:01:05.519 --> 00:01:08.520
from The Ohio State University.

00:01:08.520 --> 00:01:09.960
And here's the backstory.

00:01:09.960 --> 00:01:13.500
So when I first
met Tanya, she was

00:01:13.500 --> 00:01:15.986
working on this very
interesting project

00:01:15.986 --> 00:01:17.360
that, believe it
or not, involved

00:01:17.360 --> 00:01:19.440
a study of Fresh Choice Zoopa.

00:01:19.440 --> 00:01:22.140
And Fresh Choice, as
you probably well know,

00:01:22.140 --> 00:01:23.670
is a very trendy--

00:01:23.670 --> 00:01:24.930
or was a very trendy--

00:01:24.930 --> 00:01:27.620
West Coast salad buffet chain.

00:01:27.620 --> 00:01:31.830
But they were faced with a
stale concept, sinking sales.

00:01:31.830 --> 00:01:35.910
And they had their eye
on a very quirky Seattle

00:01:35.910 --> 00:01:38.190
competitor called Zoopa.

00:01:38.190 --> 00:01:40.770
And Zoopa had a completely
different model.

00:01:40.770 --> 00:01:42.180
Instead of having
a buffet chain,

00:01:42.180 --> 00:01:45.840
they had chefs at stations
engaging customers.

00:01:45.840 --> 00:01:46.980
What's your point?

00:01:46.980 --> 00:01:50.910
The point is that Fresh
Choice was all over Zoopa.

00:01:50.910 --> 00:01:52.890
They were looking at
their best practices.

00:01:52.890 --> 00:01:55.642
They were infiltrating
their different restaurants,

00:01:55.642 --> 00:01:56.850
learning, learning, learning.

00:01:56.850 --> 00:02:00.060
Eventually, they acquired Zoopa.

00:02:00.060 --> 00:02:02.580
And then all of a sudden,
the learning stopped.

00:02:02.580 --> 00:02:05.760
All the innovative ideas
that they initially

00:02:05.760 --> 00:02:09.759
were very excited about,
they were dismissing.

00:02:09.759 --> 00:02:11.550
So we thought, well,
this is kind of weird.

00:02:11.550 --> 00:02:12.720
What explains that?

00:02:12.720 --> 00:02:14.370
How can you be
all over something

00:02:14.370 --> 00:02:16.910
and then drop it
like a hot potato?

00:02:16.910 --> 00:02:19.800
Then I started telling Tanya
about this phenomenon that

00:02:19.800 --> 00:02:23.580
was happening in some
of my executive classes.

00:02:23.580 --> 00:02:26.384
And I kept thinking of this
crazy Woody Allen quote--

00:02:26.384 --> 00:02:28.050
"I never want to
belong to any club that

00:02:28.050 --> 00:02:29.100
would have me as a member."

00:02:29.100 --> 00:02:30.766
I just wanted to find
a way to work that

00:02:30.766 --> 00:02:32.310
into the conversation.

00:02:32.310 --> 00:02:35.730
So I've had more than
one of my executives

00:02:35.730 --> 00:02:38.100
in my management
classes say that they've

00:02:38.100 --> 00:02:41.730
had a very strange experience
in their own companies.

00:02:41.730 --> 00:02:43.170
They would have
ideas, they would

00:02:43.170 --> 00:02:45.630
have insights that
would be dismissed

00:02:45.630 --> 00:02:49.320
by their bosses,
leaders, upper managers.

00:02:49.320 --> 00:02:51.480
And then in the case of
one woman in my class,

00:02:51.480 --> 00:02:55.440
once she left her company,
started her own consulting

00:02:55.440 --> 00:02:58.260
firm, her previous
company called her

00:02:58.260 --> 00:03:02.400
and paid her four
times the money

00:03:02.400 --> 00:03:05.880
that she ever would have asked
for for her original idea.

00:03:05.880 --> 00:03:09.780
So it wasn't until
she became an outsider

00:03:09.780 --> 00:03:15.540
that all of a sudden, her ideas
seemed to get more valuation

00:03:15.540 --> 00:03:16.740
or traction.

00:03:16.740 --> 00:03:21.750
So what we're going to do today
is we're going to talk about--

00:03:21.750 --> 00:03:26.130
well, why is it the case that
sometimes what we're doing

00:03:26.130 --> 00:03:29.700
doesn't seem to add
traction to solving

00:03:29.700 --> 00:03:32.160
some of our internal problems?

00:03:32.160 --> 00:03:36.310
So sometimes, our strengths
can lead us astray.

00:03:36.310 --> 00:03:38.220
So what we're going
to do today is

00:03:38.220 --> 00:03:40.860
we're going to talk about the
winner's trap, which really

00:03:40.860 --> 00:03:43.710
comes out of this
Zoopa, Fresh Choice,

00:03:43.710 --> 00:03:45.990
we overvalue
consultants' ideas where

00:03:45.990 --> 00:03:49.410
we tend to see our
colleagues as competitors

00:03:49.410 --> 00:03:51.330
and we devalue their ideas.

00:03:51.330 --> 00:03:53.640
We're going to talk
about the expertise trap.

00:03:53.640 --> 00:03:58.290
And that's where we get so
involved in our own domain

00:03:58.290 --> 00:04:02.230
that we block learning
from other domains.

00:04:02.230 --> 00:04:05.490
We're going to talk about my
favorite one, the agreement

00:04:05.490 --> 00:04:06.150
trap.

00:04:06.150 --> 00:04:09.630
So I'm a negotiation researcher.

00:04:09.630 --> 00:04:11.730
And what I often
find is that people

00:04:11.730 --> 00:04:15.900
are extremely uncomfortable
negotiating, especially

00:04:15.900 --> 00:04:17.510
in unscripted situations.

00:04:17.510 --> 00:04:19.816
So we're going to have
some fun with that.

00:04:19.816 --> 00:04:21.399
Another favorite one
of mine is called

00:04:21.399 --> 00:04:23.850
the macro-management trap.

00:04:23.850 --> 00:04:28.950
The central idea is that we've
gotten the memo that we need

00:04:28.950 --> 00:04:32.430
to empower others and delegate.

00:04:32.430 --> 00:04:34.830
And then we take away
all the structure,

00:04:34.830 --> 00:04:36.452
and we don't put
up any guardrails.

00:04:36.452 --> 00:04:38.160
And then we're going
to talk a little bit

00:04:38.160 --> 00:04:39.600
about the communication trap.

00:04:39.600 --> 00:04:42.210
So armed with all
of our technology,

00:04:42.210 --> 00:04:45.780
the signal-to-noise ratio
is starting to be a problem.

00:04:45.780 --> 00:04:47.770
I don't expect you
to read all this.

00:04:47.770 --> 00:04:52.770
But we did a survey with a
lot of different executives,

00:04:52.770 --> 00:04:55.000
leaders, managers, et cetera.

00:04:55.000 --> 00:04:57.780
And we had them basically
say how much money

00:04:57.780 --> 00:05:01.230
do you spend each day on--

00:05:01.230 --> 00:05:03.480
how much money do
you lose each day

00:05:03.480 --> 00:05:07.860
when you are not
able to negotiate

00:05:07.860 --> 00:05:11.030
a mutually beneficial outcome.

00:05:11.030 --> 00:05:12.030
This is my favorite one.

00:05:12.030 --> 00:05:15.240
How much money would
you say is involved

00:05:15.240 --> 00:05:17.640
in unproductive
meetings-- so if you

00:05:17.640 --> 00:05:19.890
think about what is the
value of your time, how

00:05:19.890 --> 00:05:23.100
many meetings you're in.

00:05:23.100 --> 00:05:26.100
We also asked a lot
of questions about

00:05:26.100 --> 00:05:30.000
do you pay people to motivate
them to do routine work.

00:05:30.000 --> 00:05:33.060
And we asked a lot of questions
about how much money do you

00:05:33.060 --> 00:05:35.460
pay consultants versus
your own people.

00:05:35.460 --> 00:05:40.200
And the bottom line numbers
really surprised us.

00:05:40.200 --> 00:05:42.792
So on average--
these are hundreds

00:05:42.792 --> 00:05:44.250
of people that
we're interviewing--

00:05:44.250 --> 00:05:48.690
said that they spent over
$7,000 per line item per day.

00:05:48.690 --> 00:05:51.740
If you add up the cost
of this wasted time,

00:05:51.740 --> 00:05:54.190
if you add up all these
dimensions together,

00:05:54.190 --> 00:05:57.150
there's a waste of
like a $144,000 a day,

00:05:57.150 --> 00:05:59.650
and it turns out to
be $52 million a year.

00:05:59.650 --> 00:06:03.950
So what we're going
to do is we're

00:06:03.950 --> 00:06:11.200
going to unpack some of
these hidden people problems.

00:06:11.200 --> 00:06:13.190
And what we're
going to start with

00:06:13.190 --> 00:06:18.140
is the winner's trap, which is
the basis of how we got started

00:06:18.140 --> 00:06:20.210
in this whole enterprise.

00:06:20.210 --> 00:06:26.840
And the idea here is that
motivated, results-driven

00:06:26.840 --> 00:06:28.430
managers get things done.

00:06:28.430 --> 00:06:34.100
A lot of us have been programmed
to be action oriented,

00:06:34.100 --> 00:06:35.540
take charge.

00:06:35.540 --> 00:06:40.430
Sometimes, though, we may see
our colleagues as competitors.

00:06:40.430 --> 00:06:42.260
Now, what I'm
going to do next is

00:06:42.260 --> 00:06:44.690
I'm going to talk to you
about a research study.

00:06:44.690 --> 00:06:46.580
And I just want you to
make some predictions.

00:06:46.580 --> 00:06:48.510
So here's the research study.

00:06:48.510 --> 00:06:50.630
So what Professor
Menon and myself

00:06:50.630 --> 00:06:54.620
did is we wanted to
compare how people--

00:06:54.620 --> 00:06:57.260
managers, people
who have real jobs--

00:06:57.260 --> 00:06:59.280
react to good ideas--

00:06:59.280 --> 00:07:02.150
in other words,
innovative ideas--

00:07:02.150 --> 00:07:07.730
authored by internal people,
who are their colleagues,

00:07:07.730 --> 00:07:12.530
versus the exact
same idea allegedly

00:07:12.530 --> 00:07:14.240
authored by an outsider.

00:07:14.240 --> 00:07:16.170
Maybe it would be a competitor.

00:07:16.170 --> 00:07:19.100
Maybe it would be somebody
outside the company.

00:07:19.100 --> 00:07:22.310
And I'm just curious--

00:07:22.310 --> 00:07:24.470
what would be your intuition?

00:07:24.470 --> 00:07:27.890
These people are reacting
to the exact same idea.

00:07:27.890 --> 00:07:29.930
The only difference
is that I either

00:07:29.930 --> 00:07:33.320
think it's been authored
by a colleague of mine,

00:07:33.320 --> 00:07:37.340
or I think it's been authored
by maybe a competitor of mine.

00:07:37.340 --> 00:07:39.520
What would be your intuition?

00:07:39.520 --> 00:07:40.260
What's your name?

00:07:40.260 --> 00:07:41.010
AUDIENCE: Deborah.

00:07:41.010 --> 00:07:41.350
LEIGH THOMPSON: Deborah.

00:07:41.350 --> 00:07:43.120
Deborah is saying I wish you
wouldn't have call on me.

00:07:43.120 --> 00:07:44.828
So Deborah, what would
be your intuition?

00:07:44.828 --> 00:07:46.512
I've told you we
have this theory.

00:07:46.512 --> 00:07:47.470
AUDIENCE: The external.

00:07:47.470 --> 00:07:48.678
LEIGH THOMPSON: The external.

00:07:48.678 --> 00:07:50.620
Do you have any intuitions why?

00:07:50.620 --> 00:07:53.689
Why is it that we do that?

00:07:53.689 --> 00:07:54.675
AUDIENCE: I don't know.

00:07:54.675 --> 00:07:56.160
I don't have a good theory.

00:07:56.160 --> 00:07:57.870
LEIGH THOMPSON: But you
seem really quick to think

00:07:57.870 --> 00:07:58.994
we think it's the external.

00:07:58.994 --> 00:08:00.480
So something about-- OK.

00:08:00.480 --> 00:08:02.060
So this is what we found.

00:08:02.060 --> 00:08:03.510
Deborah is spot on.

00:08:03.510 --> 00:08:05.820
So what we did here-- and
I want to explain this--

00:08:05.820 --> 00:08:08.340
is we said, well,
how willing would you

00:08:08.340 --> 00:08:12.690
be to learn from this
really cool, novel idea.

00:08:12.690 --> 00:08:16.200
And we found that--
again, holding the nature,

00:08:16.200 --> 00:08:19.440
substance of the
idea constant, we

00:08:19.440 --> 00:08:23.320
are much more likely to want
to learn from outsiders' ideas

00:08:23.320 --> 00:08:24.480
than insiders' ideas.

00:08:24.480 --> 00:08:26.310
And again, I keep
on driving home--

00:08:26.310 --> 00:08:29.170
we're holding the
idea itself constant.

00:08:29.170 --> 00:08:31.432
And then we ask people, well--

00:08:31.432 --> 00:08:33.390
I asked the same question
that I asked Deborah.

00:08:33.390 --> 00:08:35.669
Why do you think this is?

00:08:35.669 --> 00:08:37.000
We asked a lot of questions.

00:08:37.000 --> 00:08:39.809
But when it came to
are you concerned

00:08:39.809 --> 00:08:42.900
that you might lose some
status in your organization

00:08:42.900 --> 00:08:47.760
if you really followed Deborah's
idea, that's when people said,

00:08:47.760 --> 00:08:50.550
yes, we think that
that could be the case.

00:08:50.550 --> 00:08:52.770
So we did a followup
study, and we

00:08:52.770 --> 00:08:56.010
found that managers
allocate 42% more budget

00:08:56.010 --> 00:08:58.020
money to learn about
outsider innovation

00:08:58.020 --> 00:09:00.180
the same way that Zoopa--

00:09:00.180 --> 00:09:02.880
the same way that Fresh
Choice did with Zoopa.

00:09:02.880 --> 00:09:06.270
But they believed that they were
36 more likely to lose status.

00:09:06.270 --> 00:09:09.820
So then what we did is we
had to try to be good social

00:09:09.820 --> 00:09:11.320
scientists, and we
had to say, look,

00:09:11.320 --> 00:09:14.490
if we're going to show something
bad about human behavior that

00:09:14.490 --> 00:09:17.970
we de-value-- our
colleagues' ideas--

00:09:17.970 --> 00:09:19.470
as good social
scientists, we should

00:09:19.470 --> 00:09:21.120
try to be able to repair this.

00:09:21.120 --> 00:09:22.170
What's the fix?

00:09:22.170 --> 00:09:23.670
What's the Band-Aid?

00:09:23.670 --> 00:09:28.560
And so we hypothesized
that maybe what's going on

00:09:28.560 --> 00:09:32.010
is this that people in
companies and organizations

00:09:32.010 --> 00:09:35.070
get into micro-competitions.

00:09:35.070 --> 00:09:38.100
Every day, I'm trying to
be smarter than Deborah.

00:09:38.100 --> 00:09:40.620
I'm trying to be
smarter than Nicky.

00:09:40.620 --> 00:09:44.520
And so if we can get people out
of these micro-competitions,

00:09:44.520 --> 00:09:46.320
maybe they'll realize,
well, Nicky really

00:09:46.320 --> 00:09:49.026
has a really cool
idea, and it's not

00:09:49.026 --> 00:09:50.400
going to cause me
to lose status.

00:09:50.400 --> 00:09:56.070
So what we did is we did a very
simple research investigation.

00:09:56.070 --> 00:10:00.120
We had some people call
to mind specific personal

00:10:00.120 --> 00:10:04.370
accomplishments that they
themselves had achieved.

00:10:04.370 --> 00:10:07.590
And other people-- we
didn't tell them to do this.

00:10:07.590 --> 00:10:10.460
And what we found
is that the people

00:10:10.460 --> 00:10:15.120
who recalled a personal
accomplishment when

00:10:15.120 --> 00:10:19.710
they heard about
Deborah's fantastic idea--

00:10:19.710 --> 00:10:22.770
they said, of course I
want to learn from Deborah.

00:10:22.770 --> 00:10:24.840
Of course I want to
acquire that knowledge,

00:10:24.840 --> 00:10:27.680
and of course I'll use it.

00:10:27.680 --> 00:10:32.240
If they didn't recall a personal
accomplishment-- no recall--

00:10:32.240 --> 00:10:34.680
they were less
likely to do that.

00:10:34.680 --> 00:10:42.440
So the takeaway message is that
we need to widen our aperture.

00:10:42.440 --> 00:10:45.890
We need to get away from the
micro, daily competitions

00:10:45.890 --> 00:10:51.020
and realize there is talent
all around me that I can use,

00:10:51.020 --> 00:10:54.320
and it doesn't mean
that, in some sense,

00:10:54.320 --> 00:10:56.850
I'm going to be a loser.

00:10:56.850 --> 00:10:58.580
So I want to ask
you the equivalent

00:10:58.580 --> 00:11:02.090
of a managerial Rorschach test.

00:11:02.090 --> 00:11:04.730
Let's imagine that these
two people work together.

00:11:04.730 --> 00:11:06.570
They're on the same team.

00:11:06.570 --> 00:11:10.820
And I want you to imagine
that the young woman we

00:11:10.820 --> 00:11:15.590
see here is the boss, or at
least the older gentleman

00:11:15.590 --> 00:11:18.040
here reports up to you.

00:11:18.040 --> 00:11:23.410
Any hypotheses about--
and let's suppose

00:11:23.410 --> 00:11:26.140
they're discussing a
very important project.

00:11:26.140 --> 00:11:30.830
Any hypotheses about what
their professional relationship

00:11:30.830 --> 00:11:31.330
is like?

00:11:31.330 --> 00:11:32.621
This is an open-ended question.

00:11:32.621 --> 00:11:34.321
Can I call on you?

00:11:34.321 --> 00:11:34.820
Yes.

00:11:34.820 --> 00:11:35.690
What's your first name?

00:11:35.690 --> 00:11:36.020
AUDIENCE: Sarah.

00:11:36.020 --> 00:11:36.936
LEIGH THOMPSON: Sarah.

00:11:36.936 --> 00:11:38.400
OK, Sarah.

00:11:38.400 --> 00:11:41.030
What do you think
is going on here?

00:11:41.030 --> 00:11:42.725
AUDIENCE: So the lady is the--

00:11:42.725 --> 00:11:45.340
SPEAKER: The lady is the boss.

00:11:45.340 --> 00:11:46.410
He reports up to her.

00:11:46.410 --> 00:11:48.840
How does he feel
about this whole--

00:11:48.840 --> 00:11:51.762
they're discussing a project.

00:11:51.762 --> 00:11:52.720
AUDIENCE: I don't know.

00:11:52.720 --> 00:11:54.310
Maybe he feels undervalued.

00:11:54.310 --> 00:11:57.150
He may be more experienced.

00:11:57.150 --> 00:11:58.980
LEIGH THOMPSON: He's
got more experience.

00:11:58.980 --> 00:12:00.420
You can look at
him and tell that.

00:12:00.420 --> 00:12:01.860
Anybody else have a--

00:12:01.860 --> 00:12:02.520
thank you.

00:12:02.520 --> 00:12:07.144
Anybody else have an intuition
about how he might feel?

00:12:07.144 --> 00:12:08.560
AUDIENCE: Like he knows better.

00:12:08.560 --> 00:12:10.890
SPEAKER: Like he knows better.

00:12:10.890 --> 00:12:14.070
So I got very
interested in this.

00:12:14.070 --> 00:12:16.080
You guys know I teach
full-time MBA students.

00:12:16.080 --> 00:12:19.920
And I cannot tell you how many
times I've had a very young

00:12:19.920 --> 00:12:23.400
28-year-old, 27-year-old
MBA student--

00:12:23.400 --> 00:12:26.880
male or female-- say one of
the most uncomfortable things

00:12:26.880 --> 00:12:30.570
about my previous job
before coming to b-school

00:12:30.570 --> 00:12:32.700
was that I had older
people on my team

00:12:32.700 --> 00:12:34.650
who were threatened by me.

00:12:34.650 --> 00:12:35.550
I was their boss.

00:12:35.550 --> 00:12:41.290
So in other words, they walk
around feeling like I'm young,

00:12:41.290 --> 00:12:44.554
I'm talented, and
older people have

00:12:44.554 --> 00:12:45.720
a hard time dealing with me.

00:12:45.720 --> 00:12:47.310
And we thought, oh my gosh.

00:12:47.310 --> 00:12:50.040
What a problem to have.

00:12:50.040 --> 00:12:52.410
I don't have that
problem, but they do.

00:12:52.410 --> 00:12:54.750
So what we did is we
thought, well, we've

00:12:54.750 --> 00:12:56.070
got to study the dang thing.

00:12:56.070 --> 00:12:59.520
So what we did is we set up a
situation where we had managers

00:12:59.520 --> 00:13:05.550
on project teams estimate how
much they threatened others,

00:13:05.550 --> 00:13:08.250
because they're so
brilliant, and so talented,

00:13:08.250 --> 00:13:09.990
and so accomplished.

00:13:09.990 --> 00:13:13.320
But we also asked them,
well, how threatened are you.

00:13:13.320 --> 00:13:15.270
And so I'm kind of curious.

00:13:15.270 --> 00:13:17.437
I'm going to call on some
of my folks over here.

00:13:17.437 --> 00:13:18.395
What's your first name?

00:13:18.395 --> 00:13:18.670
AUDIENCE: Andrew.

00:13:18.670 --> 00:13:19.890
LEIGH THOMPSON: Andrew.

00:13:19.890 --> 00:13:24.540
Do you have a hypothesis about
what we're going to find?

00:13:24.540 --> 00:13:29.690
How threatened-- people have
to say how threatened they are

00:13:29.690 --> 00:13:32.690
and how threatening
other people see them

00:13:32.690 --> 00:13:35.930
in terms of their
prowess and talent.

00:13:35.930 --> 00:13:36.930
You have that intuition?

00:13:36.930 --> 00:13:40.737
AUDIENCE: People are probably
uncomfortable with admitting

00:13:40.737 --> 00:13:41.820
that they feel threatened.

00:13:41.820 --> 00:13:42.736
SPEAKER: Say it again.

00:13:42.736 --> 00:13:46.270
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]
that they're threatened.

00:13:46.270 --> 00:13:48.431
SPEAKER: I think Andrew
is really on to something.

00:13:48.431 --> 00:13:49.930
And he said-- I'm
going to repeat it

00:13:49.930 --> 00:13:51.580
for acoustical
reasons-- he said people

00:13:51.580 --> 00:13:54.880
are uncomfortable admitting
how threatened they might be.

00:13:54.880 --> 00:13:56.440
Andrew, that's
exactly what we found.

00:13:56.440 --> 00:13:58.450
I think you have a career
as a social scientist

00:13:58.450 --> 00:14:00.710
if you're interested.

00:14:00.710 --> 00:14:03.550
So what we did-- ignore
this junk for a minute.

00:14:03.550 --> 00:14:07.480
We asked people, look,
you're on this project team.

00:14:07.480 --> 00:14:10.000
How much do you
threaten others just

00:14:10.000 --> 00:14:13.510
because you're so bad ass
and so talented, et cetera?

00:14:13.510 --> 00:14:16.420
And they said, oh, my
gosh, I'm almost a five

00:14:16.420 --> 00:14:18.910
on a five-point scale.

00:14:18.910 --> 00:14:21.660
Because I've got all
this going on for me,

00:14:21.660 --> 00:14:25.270
and it's just hard for people
to take so much of my greatness.

00:14:25.270 --> 00:14:28.729
When we flip the question,
Andrew's theory holds.

00:14:28.729 --> 00:14:30.520
We asked them, well,
how threatened are you

00:14:30.520 --> 00:14:33.280
by all these fantastic
colleagues of yours.

00:14:33.280 --> 00:14:35.440
Oh, I'm about a 3.26.

00:14:35.440 --> 00:14:37.480
So in other words,
then we started

00:14:37.480 --> 00:14:40.220
to become very interested in
this whole threat immunity

00:14:40.220 --> 00:14:40.720
thing.

00:14:40.720 --> 00:14:43.860
In other words, I
don't get ruffled

00:14:43.860 --> 00:14:47.290
that other people have a hard
time taking my greatness.

00:14:47.290 --> 00:14:50.410
And I'm overdramatizing here.

00:14:50.410 --> 00:14:53.650
So then we decided to
really dial this up,

00:14:53.650 --> 00:14:56.950
and then we published
this crazy paper called--

00:14:56.950 --> 00:14:59.590
based upon this bumper
sticker that we saw--

00:14:59.590 --> 00:15:01.240
"Don't Hate Me
Because I'm Beautiful.

00:15:01.240 --> 00:15:04.660
Hate Me Because I'm Young,"
which is the snarkiest thing

00:15:04.660 --> 00:15:06.249
that anybody could say.

00:15:06.249 --> 00:15:08.290
We don't hate you at all
because of those things.

00:15:08.290 --> 00:15:11.130
You're just annoying.

00:15:11.130 --> 00:15:12.160
And what we found--

00:15:12.160 --> 00:15:13.576
and I want you to
think about what

00:15:13.576 --> 00:15:15.340
Andrew said a few minutes ago.

00:15:15.340 --> 00:15:19.090
What we found is to the extent
that we're walking around

00:15:19.090 --> 00:15:24.686
in this little ego bubble,
where I'm so talented

00:15:24.686 --> 00:15:26.560
and I know it type of
thing, and other people

00:15:26.560 --> 00:15:28.990
have a hard time
taking my greatness--

00:15:28.990 --> 00:15:33.400
two things happen which really
can cost an organization

00:15:33.400 --> 00:15:35.110
a lot of value.

00:15:35.110 --> 00:15:36.940
One thing that
happens is that people

00:15:36.940 --> 00:15:39.460
start to dumb themselves down.

00:15:39.460 --> 00:15:43.450
Actually, about 48%
of people said, well,

00:15:43.450 --> 00:15:45.370
I've decided to hold
back a little bit,

00:15:45.370 --> 00:15:49.600
because I'm sure that people
will fall apart once I

00:15:49.600 --> 00:15:51.400
start to speak my greatness.

00:15:51.400 --> 00:15:55.690
And then we also found out
that this whole threat immunity

00:15:55.690 --> 00:15:58.460
bubble can hurt relationships.

00:15:58.460 --> 00:16:00.550
In other words,
people don't feel

00:16:00.550 --> 00:16:05.350
as collaborative and
connected on a team.

00:16:05.350 --> 00:16:12.430
So again, the key here
is that people are not

00:16:12.430 --> 00:16:13.890
that threatened by you.

00:16:13.890 --> 00:16:20.006
So we need to really speak
up and offer what we have.

00:16:20.006 --> 00:16:21.630
Now what I want to
do is I want to talk

00:16:21.630 --> 00:16:23.170
about-- question, Nikki.

00:16:23.170 --> 00:16:26.179
AUDIENCE: What about the
theory of imposter syndrome?

00:16:26.179 --> 00:16:26.970
LEIGH THOMPSON: OK.

00:16:26.970 --> 00:16:29.620
So the great question was, what
about the imposter syndrome,

00:16:29.620 --> 00:16:32.580
which is, oh, my
gosh, I'm the idiot.

00:16:32.580 --> 00:16:35.850
And sooner or later,
the organization

00:16:35.850 --> 00:16:39.220
is going to realize that
I shouldn't be here.

00:16:39.220 --> 00:16:42.960
I think that that is alive
and well and kicking.

00:16:42.960 --> 00:16:46.110
But what we don't know
is what is the base

00:16:46.110 --> 00:16:47.940
rate of the imposter syndrome.

00:16:47.940 --> 00:16:49.530
I think that a lot of times--

00:16:49.530 --> 00:16:55.500
at least qualitatively
speaking-- a lot of newcomers--

00:16:55.500 --> 00:16:58.980
like, for example, PhD
students to programs--

00:16:58.980 --> 00:17:01.110
have a little bit of
that imposter syndrome.

00:17:01.110 --> 00:17:04.560
Once they finally pass the
preliminary examinations,

00:17:04.560 --> 00:17:06.270
they dust themselves off.

00:17:06.270 --> 00:17:08.880
So I think that the
imposter syndrome

00:17:08.880 --> 00:17:11.130
is alive and well and kicking.

00:17:11.130 --> 00:17:15.510
But I don't think it's got as
big of a base rate, incidence

00:17:15.510 --> 00:17:17.250
rate as this one.

00:17:17.250 --> 00:17:19.859
So I'd love to do a study
where you take people

00:17:19.859 --> 00:17:22.890
who have this threat immunity,
put them in the same room

00:17:22.890 --> 00:17:27.582
as somebody who has the imposter
syndrome, and see what happens.

00:17:27.582 --> 00:17:29.040
So I'm going to
switch gears, and I

00:17:29.040 --> 00:17:32.400
want to talk about
this expertise trap.

00:17:32.400 --> 00:17:34.060
And the whole idea here--

00:17:34.060 --> 00:17:36.250
and I've done my own
little crossing out here--

00:17:36.250 --> 00:17:41.080
is that domain expertise
is essential these days.

00:17:41.080 --> 00:17:43.530
We're really
focused on let's get

00:17:43.530 --> 00:17:48.610
people who are hyper-talented
in what they do.

00:17:48.610 --> 00:17:50.170
And then let's
hopefully have them

00:17:50.170 --> 00:17:52.790
cross-pollinate
with other people.

00:17:52.790 --> 00:17:57.440
But I'm very interested in
this whole idea of where

00:17:57.440 --> 00:17:59.050
do you get really cool ideas.

00:17:59.050 --> 00:18:00.480
And so I'm going to show you--

00:18:00.480 --> 00:18:01.680
I wish I would have
done this study.

00:18:01.680 --> 00:18:02.490
I didn't do this study.

00:18:02.490 --> 00:18:03.570
But I'm going to tell
you about this study,

00:18:03.570 --> 00:18:05.110
because I think it's great.

00:18:05.110 --> 00:18:07.810
So this study was done by
O'Creevy and his colleagues.

00:18:07.810 --> 00:18:10.440
And what they did is they had
two groups of people sitting

00:18:10.440 --> 00:18:13.680
in front of computers, like
a Bloomberg stock trading

00:18:13.680 --> 00:18:14.550
terminal.

00:18:14.550 --> 00:18:16.620
And they were told, look,
there's a line moving,

00:18:16.620 --> 00:18:17.550
numbers updating.

00:18:17.550 --> 00:18:19.350
And they said, look, experiment.

00:18:19.350 --> 00:18:21.120
Play around with the buttons.

00:18:21.120 --> 00:18:23.190
See if you can figure
out what manipulates

00:18:23.190 --> 00:18:25.460
the movement of the line.

00:18:25.460 --> 00:18:27.320
Group 1 thought that
they were, quote,

00:18:27.320 --> 00:18:31.370
very successful in figuring out
how the buttons move the line.

00:18:31.370 --> 00:18:32.790
And these are Wall
Street traders.

00:18:32.790 --> 00:18:36.680
Group 2, which
were random people

00:18:36.680 --> 00:18:39.140
without a financial
background, quickly

00:18:39.140 --> 00:18:41.960
realized there is no
relationship between me

00:18:41.960 --> 00:18:46.220
pressing, in some
sense, the lever

00:18:46.220 --> 00:18:48.830
and what is happening
on the line.

00:18:48.830 --> 00:18:51.970
So the takeaway message that
I think O'Creevy was going for

00:18:51.970 --> 00:18:55.760
is that sometimes,
experts in a domain

00:18:55.760 --> 00:18:59.540
see things that might not
be there, or in some sense,

00:18:59.540 --> 00:19:03.600
overestimate their expertise.

00:19:03.600 --> 00:19:06.630
So my next question
for you guys is

00:19:06.630 --> 00:19:11.970
going to be where do you
get your innovative ideas.

00:19:11.970 --> 00:19:14.046
Because I'm very
interested in this.

00:19:14.046 --> 00:19:15.420
And I wanted to
tell you a story.

00:19:15.420 --> 00:19:17.250
I work with chief
security officers.

00:19:17.250 --> 00:19:20.060
I know that sounds like an
interesting group to work with,

00:19:20.060 --> 00:19:21.984
but that's who I work with.

00:19:21.984 --> 00:19:23.400
And they told me
this great story.

00:19:23.400 --> 00:19:25.872
I said, where are you guys
getting your next innovations?

00:19:25.872 --> 00:19:28.080
You're dealing with all
kinds of really challenging--

00:19:28.080 --> 00:19:31.752
cyber threats, all kinds of--

00:19:31.752 --> 00:19:32.820
bioterrorism.

00:19:32.820 --> 00:19:34.791
There's all kinds
of stuff going on.

00:19:34.791 --> 00:19:36.040
They told me this great story.

00:19:36.040 --> 00:19:40.230
They said that recently, they
did an off site at a zoo.

00:19:40.230 --> 00:19:41.790
And I said, come again?

00:19:41.790 --> 00:19:43.740
What are you guys
doing at the zoo?

00:19:43.740 --> 00:19:47.700
And they said, Leigh,
animals of every species

00:19:47.700 --> 00:19:50.220
are under constant threat.

00:19:50.220 --> 00:19:52.590
And different species
have different ways

00:19:52.590 --> 00:19:55.470
of protecting themselves
against threat.

00:19:55.470 --> 00:19:57.510
They said, we wanted
to learn about as many

00:19:57.510 --> 00:19:59.290
of these different
methods as possible.

00:19:59.290 --> 00:20:03.150
Because one of those ideas,
as crazy as it sounds,

00:20:03.150 --> 00:20:06.640
could open up an
innovation for us.

00:20:06.640 --> 00:20:08.010
Now, that sounds crazy.

00:20:08.010 --> 00:20:11.580
But I recently had a woman in
my class who, believe it or not,

00:20:11.580 --> 00:20:16.020
was designing the
suits that people--

00:20:16.020 --> 00:20:18.180
that health care
professionals have

00:20:18.180 --> 00:20:20.490
to wear dealing
with Ebola patients.

00:20:20.490 --> 00:20:22.110
This is weird.

00:20:22.110 --> 00:20:23.671
And they're designing
these suits.

00:20:23.671 --> 00:20:25.170
And you have to
stay in them all day

00:20:25.170 --> 00:20:26.628
because the patients
are coming in,

00:20:26.628 --> 00:20:28.320
and they're very comfortable.

00:20:28.320 --> 00:20:30.570
And they said, guess
who we teamed up with?

00:20:30.570 --> 00:20:33.440
I said, I can't even imagine.

00:20:33.440 --> 00:20:35.970
She said, well, women
who are getting married

00:20:35.970 --> 00:20:39.420
have to stay in the dang
wedding dress the whole day.

00:20:39.420 --> 00:20:44.250
So they got their greatest
innovation by, in some sense,

00:20:44.250 --> 00:20:47.250
going way outside their
domain, looking at-- well,

00:20:47.250 --> 00:20:48.750
let's talk about
the wedding dress.

00:20:48.750 --> 00:20:51.720
It has to look gorgeous, but
it's got to be comfortable.

00:20:51.720 --> 00:20:53.520
You've got to stay
in it the whole day.

00:20:53.520 --> 00:20:56.610
So my question to you is--

00:20:56.610 --> 00:20:57.586
what's your first name?

00:20:57.586 --> 00:20:58.260
AUDIENCE: Ed.

00:20:58.260 --> 00:20:58.710
LEIGH THOMPSON: Ed.

00:20:58.710 --> 00:20:59.876
Ed is thinking, oh, my gosh.

00:20:59.876 --> 00:21:00.932
She's coming for me.

00:21:00.932 --> 00:21:03.390
And this is a question for Ed
and anybody else in the room.

00:21:03.390 --> 00:21:07.890
If you can think of your last
cool idea or innovative idea,

00:21:07.890 --> 00:21:11.114
however large or small--

00:21:11.114 --> 00:21:12.530
can you think of
a situation where

00:21:12.530 --> 00:21:16.330
it came from outside
of a typical domain,

00:21:16.330 --> 00:21:21.577
like maybe a movie,
a wedding dress?

00:21:21.577 --> 00:21:23.114
AUDIENCE: My toddler.

00:21:23.114 --> 00:21:24.280
LEIGH THOMPSON: Say it more.

00:21:24.280 --> 00:21:25.154
AUDIENCE: My toddler.

00:21:27.785 --> 00:21:31.010
She's where I get a
lot of ideas about life

00:21:31.010 --> 00:21:34.364
because I try to make her
stop doing crazy things.

00:21:34.364 --> 00:21:35.280
LEIGH THOMPSON: Right.

00:21:35.280 --> 00:21:37.680
So you're trying to keep the
toddler like, wait a minute,

00:21:37.680 --> 00:21:38.850
we don't do things this way.

00:21:38.850 --> 00:21:40.470
So were you working on
a particular problem,

00:21:40.470 --> 00:21:43.110
Nikki, where the toddler said,
oh, I can do it with a balloon,

00:21:43.110 --> 00:21:46.260
or something?

00:21:46.260 --> 00:21:48.200
AUDIENCE: No, but that's just--

00:21:48.200 --> 00:21:52.870
or randomly just talking to
people in the micro-kitchen,

00:21:52.870 --> 00:21:58.007
we'll get an idea about how
to [INAUDIBLE] 3D printer.

00:21:58.007 --> 00:21:59.590
And then if you're
recycling, then you

00:21:59.590 --> 00:22:01.885
should just be able to recycle.

00:22:01.885 --> 00:22:04.260
LEIGH THOMPSON: First of all,
I love the fact that you're

00:22:04.260 --> 00:22:07.110
the micro-kitchen, because
we can start to now talk

00:22:07.110 --> 00:22:09.690
about collisionable
hours, running

00:22:09.690 --> 00:22:12.270
into people who
aren't necessarily

00:22:12.270 --> 00:22:14.490
in my domain of expertise.

00:22:14.490 --> 00:22:17.970
And even though they haven't
had all the years of experience

00:22:17.970 --> 00:22:20.700
you might have had, you
get a really cool idea.

00:22:20.700 --> 00:22:24.410
Anybody else have a--

00:22:24.410 --> 00:22:26.800
same, from the toddler?

00:22:26.800 --> 00:22:28.244
From the toddler.

00:22:28.244 --> 00:22:31.940
AUDIENCE: A couple of ideas
that I look at other industry--

00:22:31.940 --> 00:22:35.580
like, for example, how do
you [INAUDIBLE] process.

