how they can just quickly take

00:24:32.703 --> 00:24:34.850
it and use it without
all the knowledge,

00:24:34.850 --> 00:24:37.630
advanced knowledge of
what we were doing.

00:24:37.630 --> 00:24:38.500
LEIGH THOMPSON: OK.

00:24:38.500 --> 00:24:42.850
So in other words, that's where
the interloper, the newcomer

00:24:42.850 --> 00:24:46.940
might be a great pair
of eyes to test that.

00:24:46.940 --> 00:24:48.149
Anybody else have a similar--

00:24:48.149 --> 00:24:49.564
what's your name
in the very back?

00:24:49.564 --> 00:24:50.360
AUDIENCE: Brian.

00:24:50.360 --> 00:24:51.370
LEIGH THOMPSON: Brian.

00:24:51.370 --> 00:24:52.490
Sorry.

00:24:52.490 --> 00:24:54.860
What's your hypothesis about
the open or closed group?

00:24:54.860 --> 00:24:56.140
Because I think Boris
is on to something,

00:24:56.140 --> 00:24:58.000
but maybe you have
a different opinion.

00:24:58.000 --> 00:24:58.660
AUDIENCE: No.

00:24:58.660 --> 00:25:02.320
I feel like getting those
fresh eyes on problems

00:25:02.320 --> 00:25:04.890
is always helpful.

00:25:04.890 --> 00:25:07.022
And I try to encourage
that in my own teams.

00:25:07.022 --> 00:25:08.980
LEIGH THOMPSON: And
sometimes, it's hard to do.

00:25:08.980 --> 00:25:11.200
So here's what we found.

00:25:11.200 --> 00:25:14.290
We found-- and this
is holding constant

00:25:14.290 --> 00:25:17.050
the talent and training
level in the group.

00:25:17.050 --> 00:25:20.890
So it isn't like we brought
in certain gifted people.

00:25:20.890 --> 00:25:25.330
It was more that we just
simply reshuffled a few members

00:25:25.330 --> 00:25:26.380
in existing groups.

00:25:26.380 --> 00:25:27.160
We reshuffled.

00:25:27.160 --> 00:25:30.670
And what we found is
that the open groups

00:25:30.670 --> 00:25:32.080
generated more ideas.

00:25:32.080 --> 00:25:34.070
And our fancy word
for that is fluency.

00:25:34.070 --> 00:25:39.610
They just have a greater
proportion of per-person ideas

00:25:39.610 --> 00:25:41.380
in a fixed amount of time.

00:25:41.380 --> 00:25:45.730
And the open groups
showed more flexibility,

00:25:45.730 --> 00:25:49.900
which is our name for how many
different ideational shifts.

00:25:49.900 --> 00:25:52.330
How were they able to pivot?

00:25:52.330 --> 00:25:56.590
And so that was very
interesting for us,

00:25:56.590 --> 00:25:59.080
because we found that
a lot of times, teams

00:25:59.080 --> 00:26:01.420
like to stay intact.

00:26:01.420 --> 00:26:06.720
And the idea of inviting
in an interloper

00:26:06.720 --> 00:26:10.775
could be threatening to
the team's performance.

00:26:10.775 --> 00:26:12.400
So now we're going
to talk a little bit

00:26:12.400 --> 00:26:14.590
about the communication trap.

00:26:14.590 --> 00:26:17.020
And here's the
nature of the trap.

00:26:17.020 --> 00:26:20.080
So we're armed with
communication technology

00:26:20.080 --> 00:26:23.110
that transcends time and place.

00:26:23.110 --> 00:26:29.200
But the trap is that this very
prevalence of communication--

00:26:29.200 --> 00:26:34.030
my iPhone, and I have email,
and I have FaceTime, all this--

00:26:34.030 --> 00:26:37.370
that it might hurt the
signal-to-noise ratio.

00:26:37.370 --> 00:26:40.480
So now-- don't look
at this junk yet.

00:26:40.480 --> 00:26:42.820
Now I have a question for you.

00:26:42.820 --> 00:26:47.660
So you have been
called to facilitate

00:26:47.660 --> 00:26:51.710
an off-site by, let's
say, an unnamed company.

00:26:51.710 --> 00:26:54.860
And the unnamed company
is saying, Boris,

00:26:54.860 --> 00:26:56.510
we're having an off-site.

00:26:56.510 --> 00:27:00.740
We're going to have about
30, 35, 40 people there.

00:27:00.740 --> 00:27:04.620
We really need to dig deep,
discuss certain issues.

00:27:04.620 --> 00:27:09.470
But we're very concerned that
certain alpha dominant people

00:27:09.470 --> 00:27:11.270
might monopolize the meeting.

00:27:11.270 --> 00:27:13.670
Now you can look at the
crazy stuff up here.

00:27:13.670 --> 00:27:16.800
So when you do some research--

00:27:16.800 --> 00:27:19.730
let's take a typical
eight-person group,

00:27:19.730 --> 00:27:22.250
and let's suppose
we're videotaping

00:27:22.250 --> 00:27:26.840
in a very unobtrusive
fashion who's dominating.

00:27:26.840 --> 00:27:32.110
The most alpha, dominant person
in a typical eight-person group

00:27:32.110 --> 00:27:34.540
does about 42% of
all the talking.

00:27:34.540 --> 00:27:37.630
Stated another way,
if the faculty meeting

00:27:37.630 --> 00:27:39.700
is a 100 minutes
long, this person

00:27:39.700 --> 00:27:41.860
is talking for 42 minutes.

00:27:41.860 --> 00:27:44.380
The second most
alpha-dominant person--

00:27:44.380 --> 00:27:46.210
wow, 16%.

00:27:46.210 --> 00:27:48.730
And the rest of us are
the disenfranchised.

00:27:48.730 --> 00:27:52.930
This phenomenon is called the
uneven communication problem,

00:27:52.930 --> 00:27:56.410
and it's almost like a
law of group behavior.

00:27:56.410 --> 00:27:58.870
So this is where you come in.

00:27:58.870 --> 00:28:01.570
This unnamed company--
what's your first name?

00:28:01.570 --> 00:28:02.320
AUDIENCE: Dimitri.

00:28:02.320 --> 00:28:03.486
LEIGH THOMPSON: [INAUDIBLE]?

00:28:03.486 --> 00:28:04.310
AUDIENCE: Dimitri.

00:28:04.310 --> 00:28:05.309
LEIGH THOMPSON: Dimitri.

00:28:05.309 --> 00:28:08.110
Dimitri, we really need you.

00:28:08.110 --> 00:28:12.940
We have 35, 40 people, so we're
deathly afraid that there's

00:28:12.940 --> 00:28:15.520
going to be one, two, or three
people who really dominate

00:28:15.520 --> 00:28:16.270
this off-site.

00:28:16.270 --> 00:28:20.290
And Dimitri, money
is not an object.

00:28:20.290 --> 00:28:23.290
What can you do to
make sure that we don't

00:28:23.290 --> 00:28:25.762
have this uneven communication?

00:28:25.762 --> 00:28:27.470
And we're going to
ask other people, too.

00:28:30.690 --> 00:28:34.247
AUDIENCE: So we may split all
those people to smaller groups.

00:28:34.247 --> 00:28:35.830
LEIGH THOMPSON: I
love Dimitri's idea.

00:28:35.830 --> 00:28:38.860
He's saying let's get away
from the 35-person gang.

00:28:38.860 --> 00:28:42.820
Why don't we maybe have five
or six clusters of groups

00:28:42.820 --> 00:28:45.430
so that we can have some
simultaneous participation?

00:28:45.430 --> 00:28:48.110
I love that.

00:28:48.110 --> 00:28:48.610
Other ideas?

00:28:48.610 --> 00:28:49.746
What's your first name again?

00:28:49.746 --> 00:28:50.537
AUDIENCE: Caroline.

00:28:50.537 --> 00:28:52.080
LEIGH THOMPSON: Caroline.

00:28:52.080 --> 00:28:55.542
Money is not an object.

00:28:55.542 --> 00:28:57.500
AUDIENCE: In addition to
the small group thing,

00:28:57.500 --> 00:29:01.813
maybe mandating that each
person has a time to talk

00:29:01.813 --> 00:29:02.620
or going around.

00:29:02.620 --> 00:29:04.070
LEIGH THOMPSON: I like that.

00:29:04.070 --> 00:29:04.830
Caroline?

00:29:04.830 --> 00:29:06.250
I like what Caroline is saying.

00:29:06.250 --> 00:29:10.060
She's saying she's not going to
be passive about participation.

00:29:10.060 --> 00:29:13.840
She's going to say maybe we
need to hear from certain people

00:29:13.840 --> 00:29:15.010
that we haven't heard from.

00:29:15.010 --> 00:29:19.390
Maybe we're going to have to
play bad cop with some people.

00:29:19.390 --> 00:29:20.360
Anybody else?

00:29:20.360 --> 00:29:21.485
So far, I love these ideas.

00:29:21.485 --> 00:29:22.640
What's your first name?

00:29:22.640 --> 00:29:23.090
AUDIENCE: Alina.

00:29:23.090 --> 00:29:24.006
LEIGH THOMPSON: Alina.

00:29:24.006 --> 00:29:27.140
AUDIENCE: So what
about having laptops,

00:29:27.140 --> 00:29:30.516
tablets, whatever so that people
can send in their responses

00:29:30.516 --> 00:29:31.870
anonymously.

00:29:31.870 --> 00:29:34.230
And that way, you can't
trigger responses.

00:29:34.230 --> 00:29:35.430
Nobody feels shy.

00:29:35.430 --> 00:29:38.890
For all they know, you could
just be sitting here texting.

00:29:38.890 --> 00:29:40.540
LEIGH THOMPSON: I
love Alina's idea.

00:29:40.540 --> 00:29:43.810
She's saying maybe
the way to get

00:29:43.810 --> 00:29:48.820
more equalized participation
is to eliminate the need

00:29:48.820 --> 00:29:51.700
to dominate the verbal floor.

00:29:51.700 --> 00:29:53.900
So I think what
Alina is saying--

00:29:53.900 --> 00:29:57.650
she's suggesting a strategy
called brain writing.

00:29:57.650 --> 00:29:59.530
Alina, had you heard of that?

00:29:59.530 --> 00:30:02.855
I think you have a future
as a social scientist, too.

00:30:02.855 --> 00:30:04.480
So we're going to
get to brain writing.

00:30:04.480 --> 00:30:07.480
One company that I
know deals with this

00:30:07.480 --> 00:30:09.850
by taking a couple
of decks of cards

00:30:09.850 --> 00:30:12.100
and passing out an equal
number of cards to everybody.

00:30:12.100 --> 00:30:14.050
I don't know-- maybe
five, six, eight cards.

00:30:14.050 --> 00:30:17.590
Every time you say
something, you play a card.

00:30:17.590 --> 00:30:21.740
And once your hand is
empty, you zip it up.

00:30:21.740 --> 00:30:26.090
So you have to think, oh, am
I going to play my card here.

00:30:26.090 --> 00:30:29.430
Some companies use timers,
like the old Wizard of Oz.

00:30:29.430 --> 00:30:31.920
Once you've set a certain
number of minutes,

00:30:31.920 --> 00:30:34.060
some people use facilitators.

00:30:34.060 --> 00:30:36.260
I think Caroline would
make a great facilitator.

00:30:36.260 --> 00:30:39.290
And then Alina has
said, why don't we

00:30:39.290 --> 00:30:41.660
stop all the verbal domination.

00:30:41.660 --> 00:30:45.260
Why don't we give everybody
a laptop or the equivalent,

00:30:45.260 --> 00:30:47.300
and have them be able
to post their ideas?

00:30:47.300 --> 00:30:49.730
So anybody in this room--

00:30:49.730 --> 00:30:52.130
Dimitri, anybody ever
heard of brain writing?

00:30:52.130 --> 00:30:54.080
It's not a trick question.

00:30:54.080 --> 00:30:54.620
OK, good.

00:30:54.620 --> 00:30:56.510
OK, I got Sam right here.

00:30:56.510 --> 00:30:59.900
So brain writing is
not brainstorming.

00:30:59.900 --> 00:31:01.750
I love brainstorming.

00:31:01.750 --> 00:31:03.680
I've done a lot of
research on it myself.

00:31:03.680 --> 00:31:07.040
But brain writing
is even better.

00:31:07.040 --> 00:31:10.460
Brain writing is the
simultaneous generation

00:31:10.460 --> 00:31:13.940
of written ideas by
individuals in a group.

00:31:13.940 --> 00:31:17.600
And when I use this
technique, I have two rules--

00:31:17.600 --> 00:31:19.880
no guessing and no confessions.

00:31:19.880 --> 00:31:21.950
I'm not exactly
sure what she means.

00:31:21.950 --> 00:31:24.950
Let's say I was working with
a corporate travel group.

00:31:24.950 --> 00:31:27.080
And let's say that
they were trying

00:31:27.080 --> 00:31:30.770
to brainstorm ways of using
social media to increase

00:31:30.770 --> 00:31:31.820
corporate travel sales.

00:31:31.820 --> 00:31:33.680
Let's just say that.

00:31:33.680 --> 00:31:35.660
Let's say there were 30 people.

00:31:35.660 --> 00:31:40.370
I brought in 1,500 index
cards, three-by-five cards.

00:31:40.370 --> 00:31:41.660
I passed them out.

00:31:41.660 --> 00:31:45.460
And I said, for the next 10
minutes, complete silence.

00:31:45.460 --> 00:31:47.560
Everybody write down
all of your ideas

00:31:47.560 --> 00:31:51.160
for this corporate
social media travel idea.

00:31:51.160 --> 00:31:54.700
If you have 12
ideas, take 12 cards.

00:31:54.700 --> 00:31:57.370
If you have 15 ideas--
you guys are with me?

00:31:57.370 --> 00:31:59.950
So in other words, every
single idea of yours

00:31:59.950 --> 00:32:01.600
is on its own card.

00:32:01.600 --> 00:32:04.030
Don't sign your
name on the card.

00:32:04.030 --> 00:32:05.680
That's the no confessions part.

00:32:05.680 --> 00:32:09.520
Because when we tape the cards
on the wall, step three--

00:32:09.520 --> 00:32:13.780
after writing
individually, posting--

00:32:13.780 --> 00:32:16.390
step three is everybody
gets five post-it notes,

00:32:16.390 --> 00:32:19.650
and you vote for the five
ideas you find most exciting.

00:32:19.650 --> 00:32:22.160
And you can't say, well,
I bet Alina's idea is

00:32:22.160 --> 00:32:23.890
the third from the left.

00:32:23.890 --> 00:32:24.390
No.

00:32:24.390 --> 00:32:26.550
You cannot try to
guess who said what,

00:32:26.550 --> 00:32:30.070
because it's a
meritocracy of ideas.

00:32:30.070 --> 00:32:32.350
I don't know whose
idea I'm voting for,

00:32:32.350 --> 00:32:34.260
but I think that
that's cool, and that

00:32:34.260 --> 00:32:35.970
will move our project forward.

00:32:35.970 --> 00:32:41.820
When we did this strategy,
the group generated 228 ideas

00:32:41.820 --> 00:32:43.230
in 10 minutes.

00:32:43.230 --> 00:32:45.210
According to the
research, if we were

00:32:45.210 --> 00:32:47.640
to have gone around
the proverbial table,

00:32:47.640 --> 00:32:50.410
we never would have gotten
past the second idea,

00:32:50.410 --> 00:32:53.190
especially if it came from
the chief marketing officer.

00:32:53.190 --> 00:32:55.470
Because then everybody
would have been saying,

00:32:55.470 --> 00:32:58.140
sounds good to me.

00:32:58.140 --> 00:33:01.560
Now let me talk about some data.

00:33:01.560 --> 00:33:04.090
So what we have here
is a meta-analysis,

00:33:04.090 --> 00:33:07.650
which means you
take several dozen--

00:33:07.650 --> 00:33:10.880
almost approaching
100-- research studies.

00:33:10.880 --> 00:33:13.070
And then let's
compare brainstorming,

00:33:13.070 --> 00:33:16.250
which is, in some sense,
a verbal free-for-all.

00:33:16.250 --> 00:33:16.910
I love those.

00:33:16.910 --> 00:33:20.120
Everybody say anything
about a certain project

00:33:20.120 --> 00:33:23.870
without regard to
feasibility or expense.

00:33:23.870 --> 00:33:27.650
And then let's compare
it to brain writing.

00:33:27.650 --> 00:33:30.500
And let's have-- what's
your first name again?

00:33:30.500 --> 00:33:31.340
AUDIENCE: Dan.

00:33:31.340 --> 00:33:35.590
LEIGH THOMPSON: Let's have
Dan start us off and say--

00:33:35.590 --> 00:33:39.050
actually, let's get a
neutral, third-party judge

00:33:39.050 --> 00:33:42.440
who's blind to whose
ideas she's evaluating,

00:33:42.440 --> 00:33:45.300
and she just kind of calls it.

00:33:45.300 --> 00:33:50.630
Dan, do you have an intuition
or a hypothesis in terms

00:33:50.630 --> 00:33:56.610
of quantity and
quality as to which--

00:33:56.610 --> 00:33:58.210
where you'd put your money?

00:33:58.210 --> 00:34:00.980
AUDIENCE: Well, I've never
heard of brain writing,

00:34:00.980 --> 00:34:02.090
but I'm sure it's better.

00:34:02.090 --> 00:34:06.464
Because some people
are reluctant to talk.

00:34:06.464 --> 00:34:07.380
LEIGH THOMPSON: Right.

00:34:07.380 --> 00:34:09.760
Maybe you'll judge me.

00:34:09.760 --> 00:34:11.449
And I'm an imposter, anyway.

00:34:11.449 --> 00:34:13.138
AUDIENCE: You're
doing it anonymously.

00:34:13.138 --> 00:34:14.929
LEIGH THOMPSON: We're
doing it anonymously,

00:34:14.929 --> 00:34:17.260
because I enforce
that no guessing rule.

00:34:17.260 --> 00:34:19.190
So Dan, am I hearing
you correctly

00:34:19.190 --> 00:34:22.400
that you would say that the
brain writing groups would

00:34:22.400 --> 00:34:24.889
have greater quantity
and greater quality

00:34:24.889 --> 00:34:27.500
than our brainstormers?

00:34:27.500 --> 00:34:30.389
I think you have a career
as a social scientist, too.

00:34:30.389 --> 00:34:30.889
No, I do.

00:34:30.889 --> 00:34:33.320
I've never had anybody come
out of the gate with that.

00:34:33.320 --> 00:34:34.940
Well, Dan is exactly right.

00:34:34.940 --> 00:34:38.389
So when you look at this,
the brain writing groups

00:34:38.389 --> 00:34:42.350
are generating about 2 and
1/2 times the volume of ideas.

00:34:42.350 --> 00:34:44.360
Now, maybe they're crappy ideas.

00:34:44.360 --> 00:34:47.760
But then when you have a
neutral, third-party judge

00:34:47.760 --> 00:34:50.690
who's statistically blind
to whose ideas he or she is

00:34:50.690 --> 00:34:53.270
evaluating, there's a
significantly greater

00:34:53.270 --> 00:34:56.670
percentage of those ideas
deemed to be of value.

00:34:56.670 --> 00:35:03.910
So to me, the
takeaway is when we

00:35:03.910 --> 00:35:08.200
are on the hunt for innovation,
the last thing we want to do

00:35:08.200 --> 00:35:09.790
is have barriers to entry.

00:35:09.790 --> 00:35:13.750
So that's why I
love Alina's idea.

00:35:13.750 --> 00:35:15.650
Now, speaking of-- yes, sir.

00:35:15.650 --> 00:35:16.900
AUDIENCE: Question about that.

00:35:16.900 --> 00:35:18.550
So it's the product
of those that's

00:35:18.550 --> 00:35:20.210
the most important thing.

00:35:20.210 --> 00:35:22.800
It's the number of ideas
times-- the number of good ideas

00:35:22.800 --> 00:35:24.515
that we want to maximize.

00:35:24.515 --> 00:35:25.640
LEIGH THOMPSON: In the end.

00:35:25.640 --> 00:35:26.050
AUDIENCE: Yes.

00:35:26.050 --> 00:35:27.175
LEIGH THOMPSON: In the end.

00:35:27.175 --> 00:35:29.400
But one of the
things that we find

00:35:29.400 --> 00:35:33.970
is that too often, groups
want to put that quality

00:35:33.970 --> 00:35:36.310
criterion out there.

00:35:36.310 --> 00:35:38.290
And we want them--

00:35:38.290 --> 00:35:40.810
at least upstream in
the innovative process--

00:35:40.810 --> 00:35:43.070
to be ready to put the
rubble on the table.

00:35:43.070 --> 00:35:45.317
So what I tell a lot of
my students and executives

00:35:45.317 --> 00:35:47.400
is the way you're going
to get to dime and a ruby,

00:35:47.400 --> 00:35:51.700
a sapphire, and a rare gem
is to have a lot of ideas

00:35:51.700 --> 00:35:55.360
and have some
principle of selection.

00:35:55.360 --> 00:35:57.490
So the answer is yes.

00:35:57.490 --> 00:36:01.150
But a lot of times, groups
so quickly go to quality.

00:36:01.150 --> 00:36:04.210
And that's, again, what
we study in this book.

00:36:04.210 --> 00:36:06.100
I've been trained
to be high quality.

00:36:06.100 --> 00:36:10.990
I've been trained to
rip ideas to shreds.

00:36:10.990 --> 00:36:15.070
But there's always a time
and a place for that.

00:36:15.070 --> 00:36:18.470
We must be very
obsessed with off-sites.

00:36:18.470 --> 00:36:21.790
And I'm going to have you
make a prediction here, too.

00:36:21.790 --> 00:36:25.300
So our observation that
management off-sites often

00:36:25.300 --> 00:36:27.190
have brag sessions--
and that's not the words

00:36:27.190 --> 00:36:29.080
they use, but they often
have periods of time

00:36:29.080 --> 00:36:30.538
where people stand
up and they talk

00:36:30.538 --> 00:36:33.520
about a lot of great
things that they've done.

00:36:33.520 --> 00:36:39.230
And we started to
wonder whether talking

00:36:39.230 --> 00:36:45.300
about a self-enhancing
moment, a moment of pride,

00:36:45.300 --> 00:36:49.230
versus an embarrassing
incident might help creativity.

00:36:49.230 --> 00:36:52.620
So we did a controlled
research study.

00:36:52.620 --> 00:36:54.270
We actually did
this two times, one

00:36:54.270 --> 00:36:56.850
with teams of senior
leaders and another time

00:36:56.850 --> 00:36:58.890
with a group of
much younger people.

00:36:58.890 --> 00:37:01.110
And we had them, right
before brainstorm,

00:37:01.110 --> 00:37:06.930
either share a moment of pride
or a moment of embarrassment.

00:37:06.930 --> 00:37:13.950
And I'm very interested in what
would be your predictions here.

00:37:13.950 --> 00:37:15.150
Sam, what do you think?

00:37:15.150 --> 00:37:16.748
You're a social scientist.

00:37:19.495 --> 00:37:25.580
And it's going to be all about
how many ideas that they create

00:37:25.580 --> 00:37:27.800
without regard to feasibility.

00:37:27.800 --> 00:37:30.520
AUDIENCE: My guess would
be that the one bragging.

00:37:30.520 --> 00:37:31.910
LEIGH THOMPSON: The bragging?

00:37:31.910 --> 00:37:32.409
OK.

00:37:32.409 --> 00:37:34.190
So the bragging folks--

00:37:34.190 --> 00:37:36.620
maybe it's because-- OK.

00:37:36.620 --> 00:37:38.630
You think differently.

00:37:38.630 --> 00:37:40.700
What do you think, Heather?

00:37:40.700 --> 00:37:43.713
AUDIENCE: So I think the
embarrassing incident.

00:37:43.713 --> 00:37:46.840
Because a lot of
times, people are

00:37:46.840 --> 00:37:50.360
afraid that their idea may
not have enough quality.

00:37:50.360 --> 00:37:52.325
And so by having
somebody who they

00:37:52.325 --> 00:37:56.780
see as being successful
showing that they have not

00:37:56.780 --> 00:38:00.240
set successful limits but
were still successful,

00:38:00.240 --> 00:38:04.047
will free people up to
share more freely, I think.

00:38:04.047 --> 00:38:04.880
LEIGH THOMPSON: Wow.

00:38:04.880 --> 00:38:07.040
I love your intuition there.

00:38:07.040 --> 00:38:10.240
So in other words, if I have
the chief marketing officer,

00:38:10.240 --> 00:38:12.830
the senior vice president,
whoever it might be,

00:38:12.830 --> 00:38:14.840
talk about an
embarrassing moment--

00:38:14.840 --> 00:38:16.990
a foible, a flaw--

00:38:16.990 --> 00:38:20.210
then I'm not going to
hold back on my idea.

00:38:20.210 --> 00:38:23.270
Because what can be worse
than what you just said?

00:38:23.270 --> 00:38:26.330
So that's pretty much exactly
what we found, Heather.

00:38:26.330 --> 00:38:28.160
And the way to read
these crazy data

00:38:28.160 --> 00:38:31.580
is that we've cooked up
a creativity score which

00:38:31.580 --> 00:38:36.740
is a combination of
fluency, flexibility, volume

00:38:36.740 --> 00:38:38.350
times quality.

00:38:38.350 --> 00:38:40.310
And what we found
is that the groups

00:38:40.310 --> 00:38:44.990
who recounted an embarrassing
moment had more ideas--

00:38:44.990 --> 00:38:49.250
fluency is our fancy word
for volume per person ideas--

00:38:49.250 --> 00:38:51.500
and they made more pivots.

00:38:51.500 --> 00:38:55.610
They experimented with
different kinds of ideas

00:38:55.610 --> 00:38:57.700
than the self-enhancer.

00:38:57.700 --> 00:39:00.710
So now what I do is every
time I lead an off-site,

00:39:00.710 --> 00:39:04.190
I actually have people
share an embarrassing story.

00:39:04.190 --> 00:39:05.390
And it seems weird.

00:39:05.390 --> 00:39:07.070
But pretty soon,
everybody is laughing,

00:39:07.070 --> 00:39:09.110
exactly the way
Heather predicted.

00:39:09.110 --> 00:39:12.620
And all of a sudden,
the guard is down,

00:39:12.620 --> 00:39:16.500
and we can start putting a lot
of things out on the. table.

00:39:16.500 --> 00:39:20.310
So I want to talk about
the macro-management trap.

00:39:20.310 --> 00:39:22.740
And the whole idea
here is that managers

00:39:22.740 --> 00:39:27.390
are told to empower others, but
sometimes, they remove too much

00:39:27.390 --> 00:39:29.100
in the name of empowerment.

00:39:29.100 --> 00:39:32.520
And by the way, if I hear one
more person, one more company

00:39:32.520 --> 00:39:36.300
say our rule is that we have
no rules, I will scream.

00:39:36.300 --> 00:39:38.550
Because those studies
have been done.

00:39:38.550 --> 00:39:43.560
If you take away all the
rules, people freeze in place.

00:39:43.560 --> 00:39:47.640
Because it's like being at the
dinner table, and I'm not sure

00:39:47.640 --> 00:39:49.350
which fork to pick up.

00:39:49.350 --> 00:39:51.690
Because there are
no rules, so I'm

00:39:51.690 --> 00:39:53.280
waiting to see
what Caroline does.

00:39:53.280 --> 00:39:55.680
And Caroline is waiting
to see what I do.

00:39:55.680 --> 00:39:57.360
And no one is doing anything.

00:39:57.360 --> 00:39:59.970
So one of the
things that we have

00:39:59.970 --> 00:40:03.270
witnessed over the
year-- and I apologize.

00:40:03.270 --> 00:40:05.580
This is shock value,
and I apologize.

00:40:05.580 --> 00:40:07.800
So we're very
interested in teams.

00:40:07.800 --> 00:40:09.990
Heather knows how
interested I am in teams.

00:40:09.990 --> 00:40:12.000
And I'm interested
in team composition,

00:40:12.000 --> 00:40:14.040
and I'm interested in team size.

00:40:14.040 --> 00:40:15.960
And we have found,
in our own research,

00:40:15.960 --> 00:40:20.730
that the average team
size-- this is self-report--

00:40:20.730 --> 00:40:24.870
has increased over the years.

00:40:24.870 --> 00:40:27.600
The current average team
size in our database

00:40:27.600 --> 00:40:28.707
is about 13 people.

00:40:28.707 --> 00:40:30.290
And some of you might
be saying, well,

00:40:30.290 --> 00:40:31.680
that sounds like a nice number.

00:40:31.680 --> 00:40:34.530
What's wrong with 13 people?

00:40:34.530 --> 00:40:37.830
Well, I will tell you that big
teams are less cohesive, less

00:40:37.830 --> 00:40:42.780
satisfied, less cooperative,
and they have lower per-person

00:40:42.780 --> 00:40:43.620
productivity.

00:40:43.620 --> 00:40:48.060
There's something about having
the smallest number of people

00:40:48.060 --> 00:40:49.950
necessary to
accomplish the task.

00:40:49.950 --> 00:40:53.220
I'm going to share some of
my favorite rules of thumb.

00:40:53.220 --> 00:40:54.939
Our friend Jeff Bezos, Amazon--

00:40:54.939 --> 00:40:55.980
you guys have heard this.

00:40:55.980 --> 00:40:58.260
Our Seattle people
have heard this.

00:40:58.260 --> 00:40:59.970
He has a two pizza rule.

00:40:59.970 --> 00:41:05.030
If he cannot feed his team with
two pizzas, maybe it's too big.

00:41:05.030 --> 00:41:07.250
And these are not Chicago
deep-dish style pizzas.

00:41:07.250 --> 00:41:09.320
That would feed
several football teams.

00:41:09.320 --> 00:41:12.590
AT&amp;T, phone company-- maybe
seven plus or minus two people,

00:41:12.590 --> 00:41:14.720
like a phone number.

00:41:14.720 --> 00:41:17.930
SAP restricted their 20,000
employees to teams of 8 to 12.

00:41:21.490 --> 00:41:25.330
And that's why I really like
Dimitri's idea, a few moments

00:41:25.330 --> 00:41:29.410
back, of let's split up
this 30-person group.

00:41:29.410 --> 00:41:36.910
Because if I am not providing
some guardrails as the leader,

00:41:36.910 --> 00:41:38.909
our teams are going to become--

00:41:38.909 --> 00:41:40.450
we have a recent
paper called "What's

00:41:40.450 --> 00:41:45.610
Your Team BMI," how many
people are on your team.

00:41:45.610 --> 00:41:49.210
Now, I'm very interested,
being at a tech company,

00:41:49.210 --> 00:41:53.260
to talk about
communication technology.

00:41:53.260 --> 00:41:56.789
Rule number one up here
we do at dinner parties,

00:41:56.789 --> 00:41:58.330
but we may not do
this at the office.

00:41:58.330 --> 00:42:01.715
It says when meeting face to
face, put away technology.

00:42:01.715 --> 00:42:02.215
Why?

00:42:02.215 --> 00:42:04.400
Why would I want to
put away my technology

00:42:04.400 --> 00:42:06.282
if I was having a
meeting with Dan?

00:42:06.282 --> 00:42:07.490
Why on earth would I do that?

00:42:07.490 --> 00:42:10.820
Maybe I want to be able
to get a phone call.

00:42:10.820 --> 00:42:11.690
Any--

00:42:11.690 --> 00:42:13.190
AUDIENCE: You're
only half engaged.

00:42:13.190 --> 00:42:14.773
LEIGH THOMPSON: I'm
only half engaged.

00:42:14.773 --> 00:42:17.330
Because maybe this
thing is going to ring.

00:42:17.330 --> 00:42:19.460
So what happens to
the relationship

00:42:19.460 --> 00:42:22.760
that Dan and I might have
as colleagues when there's

00:42:22.760 --> 00:42:26.450
a cell phone on the table,
turned off, between the two

00:42:26.450 --> 00:42:27.030
of us.

00:42:27.030 --> 00:42:29.960
Do you have a
hypothesis about that?

00:42:29.960 --> 00:42:31.565
AUDIENCE: A lower
level of trust.

00:42:31.565 --> 00:42:32.690
LEIGH THOMPSON: Absolutely.

00:42:32.690 --> 00:42:34.370
So they did a recent
study where they

00:42:34.370 --> 00:42:36.120
had two people communicating.

00:42:36.120 --> 00:42:37.550
There was a
turned-off cell phone

00:42:37.550 --> 00:42:41.300
versus, I think, in another
situation, a spiral notebook.

00:42:41.300 --> 00:42:44.360
There's lower trust,
less cohesion.

00:42:44.360 --> 00:42:47.245
So that's why we say
put away the technology.

00:42:47.245 --> 00:42:48.620
I think that this
is interesting.

00:42:48.620 --> 00:42:52.940
The CEO of SuccessFactors
said two new rules--

00:42:52.940 --> 00:42:54.810
stop the blind carbon copying.

00:42:57.390 --> 00:43:00.600
So in other words,
BCC is not allowed.

00:43:00.600 --> 00:43:03.510
And if anyone else complains
about a team member,

00:43:03.510 --> 00:43:05.840
he brings them into the loop.

00:43:05.840 --> 00:43:09.200
I'm also very interested
on email boundaries.

00:43:09.200 --> 00:43:12.560
One unnamed consulting firm
that I have worked with

00:43:12.560 --> 00:43:19.430
says you do not send emails
to team members before 7:00 AM

00:43:19.430 --> 00:43:23.960
or after 5:00 PM, and
certainly not on the weekends.

00:43:23.960 --> 00:43:26.020
You're nodding your head.

00:43:26.020 --> 00:43:28.008
Nikki, good rule?

00:43:28.008 --> 00:43:30.150
AUDIENCE: We tried to
have it on our last team.

00:43:30.150 --> 00:43:31.233
LEIGH THOMPSON: You tried?

00:43:31.233 --> 00:43:33.040
It sounds like a
past tense statement.

00:43:33.040 --> 00:43:33.998
You tried to have that.

00:43:33.998 --> 00:43:35.980
Because some of us just
can't stop ourselves.

00:43:35.980 --> 00:43:36.550
Yes?

00:43:36.550 --> 00:43:38.216
AUDIENCE: There's two
things about that.

00:43:38.216 --> 00:43:41.069
One is time zones mess with
that, make it difficult.

00:43:41.069 --> 00:43:43.610
LEIGH THOMPSON: Time zones mess
with that, especially outside

00:43:43.610 --> 00:43:44.740
of the United States.

00:43:44.740 --> 00:43:47.050
AUDIENCE: And also,
technology makes it--

00:43:47.050 --> 00:43:48.860
doesn't make it
easier to do this.

00:43:48.860 --> 00:43:50.466
Sometimes I have
ideas off hours,

00:43:50.466 --> 00:43:52.090
and the technology
doesn't make it easy

00:43:52.090 --> 00:43:54.084
for me to put that
down and not send it.

00:43:54.084 --> 00:43:55.000
LEIGH THOMPSON: Right.

00:43:55.000 --> 00:43:59.740
So there could be
some hurdles for that.

00:43:59.740 --> 00:44:04.720
I do think it's interesting
that one organization that we

00:44:04.720 --> 00:44:05.729
work with has--

00:44:05.729 --> 00:44:08.020
this is a little bit different
than what you're saying,

00:44:08.020 --> 00:44:10.570
but it's something
that I do myself--

00:44:10.570 --> 00:44:15.650
nothing but good news and
updates delivered via email.

00:44:15.650 --> 00:44:19.590
In other words, if
you have a problem,

00:44:19.590 --> 00:44:22.710
do this or knock on my door.

00:44:22.710 --> 00:44:23.860
So I'm kind of curious.

00:44:23.860 --> 00:44:27.180
What is your intuition about--
why would they say nothing

00:44:27.180 --> 00:44:29.520
but good news and
updates via email?

00:44:29.520 --> 00:44:32.764
Why would they say that, Alina?

00:44:32.764 --> 00:44:34.741
AUDIENCE: Quicker
response rates, people

00:44:34.741 --> 00:44:36.494
actually check the emails.

00:44:36.494 --> 00:44:37.910
LEIGH THOMPSON:
Well, what happens

00:44:37.910 --> 00:44:40.080
if I send you an
email saying I really

00:44:40.080 --> 00:44:42.080
don't like what you said
in the faculty meeting,

00:44:42.080 --> 00:44:44.090
and I would kindly
remind you to--

00:44:44.090 --> 00:44:46.100
AUDIENCE: It's very
passive aggressive.

00:44:46.100 --> 00:44:47.020
[INAUDIBLE]

00:44:47.020 --> 00:44:49.299
LEIGH THOMPSON: It's
very passive aggressive.

00:44:49.299 --> 00:44:50.590
What do you guys think of that?

00:44:50.590 --> 00:44:51.590
Remind me of your first name.

00:44:51.590 --> 00:44:52.140
AUDIENCE: Sarah.

00:44:52.140 --> 00:44:54.223
LEIGH THOMPSON: Sarah,
what do you think about it?

00:44:54.223 --> 00:44:56.576
Was that a good rule to
have, or it it please, just--

00:44:56.576 --> 00:44:58.200
AUDIENCE: I feel like
it's common sense

00:44:58.200 --> 00:45:02.400
to deal with issues
more face-to-face.

00:45:02.400 --> 00:45:05.109
There's a lot of hidden messages
people read into emails.

00:45:05.109 --> 00:45:06.650
LEIGH THOMPSON: And
what do we know--

00:45:06.650 --> 00:45:09.890
what's your intuition about
how social behavior changes

00:45:09.890 --> 00:45:13.430
when communicating via
information technology

00:45:13.430 --> 00:45:14.220
or email?

00:45:14.220 --> 00:45:14.990
Nikki?

00:45:14.990 --> 00:45:16.990
AUDIENCE: If the rules
was nothing but good news

00:45:16.990 --> 00:45:18.650
or updates delivered
via email, you're

00:45:18.650 --> 00:45:20.480
forcing the assumption
that everyone

00:45:20.480 --> 00:45:23.230
has positive intents if it's
coming through an email,

00:45:23.230 --> 00:45:26.200
so it takes a lot of the
miscommunication out of intent

00:45:26.200 --> 00:45:27.065
from emails.

00:45:27.065 --> 00:45:27.940
LEIGH THOMPSON: Good.

00:45:27.940 --> 00:45:28.670
Right.

00:45:28.670 --> 00:45:29.730
Absolutely right.

00:45:29.730 --> 00:45:34.100
So people don't have to
deconstruct the email.

00:45:34.100 --> 00:45:37.390
And we also know
about social behavior

00:45:37.390 --> 00:45:40.460
that when you send
me a neutral message,

00:45:40.460 --> 00:45:42.350
I interpret it as negative.

00:45:42.350 --> 00:45:45.800
When you send me a
negative message,

00:45:45.800 --> 00:45:48.140
then I tend to flame back.

00:45:48.140 --> 00:45:51.080
So I've adopted this
strategy in my own life.

00:45:51.080 --> 00:45:52.520
I have a problem
with something, I

00:45:52.520 --> 00:45:56.660
am going to try to have a
synchronous communication.

00:45:56.660 --> 00:45:59.624
So now I want to talk about, in
some sense, my favorite trap,

00:45:59.624 --> 00:46:00.790
which is the agreement trap.

00:46:00.790 --> 00:46:02.690
And I want to share one
of my favorite quotes

00:46:02.690 --> 00:46:05.660
by Eldridge Cleaver, who said
"too much agreement kills

00:46:05.660 --> 00:46:08.080
a chat."

00:46:08.080 --> 00:46:09.280
I'm dying to know.

00:46:09.280 --> 00:46:11.410
Boris, you're
always here for us.

00:46:11.410 --> 00:46:13.760
What does he mean by this?

00:46:13.760 --> 00:46:16.000
And by the way, not only
what does he mean, but is

00:46:16.000 --> 00:46:19.030
that a good assumption to make?

00:46:19.030 --> 00:46:21.890
What does he mean, too much
agreement kills a chat?

00:46:21.890 --> 00:46:24.400
AUDIENCE: Sounds like people
don't challenge each other.

00:46:24.400 --> 00:46:26.400
LEIGH THOMPSON: They don't
challenge each other.

00:46:26.400 --> 00:46:29.066
So why don't I want to live in a
world where I'm not challenged?

00:46:29.066 --> 00:46:30.940
It actually might be
a lot more convenient.

00:46:30.940 --> 00:46:32.350
I'm tired of being challenged.

00:46:32.350 --> 00:46:34.030
AUDIENCE: You're
not going to grow.

00:46:34.030 --> 00:46:35.613
LEIGH THOMPSON: I'm
not going to grow.

00:46:35.613 --> 00:46:36.484
Right?

00:46:36.484 --> 00:46:37.497
What's that, Alina?

00:46:37.497 --> 00:46:38.830
AUDIENCE: Nothing new will come.

00:46:38.830 --> 00:46:40.538
LEIGH THOMPSON: Nothing
new will come up,

00:46:40.538 --> 00:46:42.580
because I'll play it safe.

00:46:42.580 --> 00:46:44.369
And you'll play it safe.

00:46:44.369 --> 00:46:45.910
And then we're going
to get bypassed.

00:46:48.490 --> 00:46:50.620
So how do I set up--

00:46:50.620 --> 00:46:51.940
I don't know-- a culture?

00:46:51.940 --> 00:46:54.580
Let's say how do I
set up my team so

00:46:54.580 --> 00:46:58.411
that we can have a good chat.

00:46:58.411 --> 00:47:00.160
What can we-- remind
me of your name, sir.

00:47:00.160 --> 00:47:00.914
AUDIENCE: Brian.

00:47:00.914 --> 00:47:02.080
LEIGH THOMPSON: Brian, yeah.

00:47:02.080 --> 00:47:04.780
How can I set up my team so we
can have a good chat, Eldridge

00:47:04.780 --> 00:47:05.612
Cleaver style?

00:47:08.710 --> 00:47:10.200
I'm not trying to trick anybody.

00:47:10.200 --> 00:47:11.509
Alina has got-- Alina knows.

00:47:11.509 --> 00:47:13.300
AUDIENCE: So this makes
me think of improv.

00:47:13.300 --> 00:47:17.770
There's the yes and rule, where
you're basically like, yes,

00:47:17.770 --> 00:47:20.100
and then you have
to build up on it.

00:47:20.100 --> 00:47:21.850
You can't ever say
no and just stop.

00:47:21.850 --> 00:47:22.766
LEIGH THOMPSON: Right.

00:47:22.766 --> 00:47:24.430
So I'm not saying no, but.

00:47:24.430 --> 00:47:26.000
I'm saying yes, and.

00:47:26.000 --> 00:47:29.020
So maybe one of the ways
we can have a good chat

00:47:29.020 --> 00:47:33.010
is to use some yes anding.

00:47:33.010 --> 00:47:34.610
So I want to talk about--

00:47:34.610 --> 00:47:35.361
here's one of my--

00:47:35.361 --> 00:47:36.859
I wish I would have
done this study.

00:47:36.859 --> 00:47:37.939
I didn't, but I love it.

00:47:37.939 --> 00:47:39.480
But you guys can
predict the results.

00:47:42.460 --> 00:47:45.210
I want you to predict
which pair of people--

00:47:45.210 --> 00:47:48.280
and imagine there were
several observations.

00:47:48.280 --> 00:47:49.475
So we get newlywed couples.

00:47:49.475 --> 00:47:51.600
Presumably, these people
love each other very much,

00:47:51.600 --> 00:47:55.640
and they're going to spend many,
many years with each other.

00:47:55.640 --> 00:47:58.150
But then in some sense,
our control group

00:47:58.150 --> 00:48:00.760
is people who are
previously unacquainted.

00:48:00.760 --> 00:48:04.960
Maybe they're people of the
same generation and background,

00:48:04.960 --> 00:48:06.460
but they're previously
unacquainted.

00:48:06.460 --> 00:48:11.050
And let's say they're
doing a negotiation,

00:48:11.050 --> 00:48:13.510
or they have to
do a negotiation.

00:48:13.510 --> 00:48:16.210
Which one of these
would you put your money

00:48:16.210 --> 00:48:18.970
on for reaching a
win-win agreement?

00:48:18.970 --> 00:48:20.243
And remind me of your name.

00:48:20.243 --> 00:48:20.950
AUDIENCE: Ed.

00:48:20.950 --> 00:48:21.520
LEIGH THOMPSON: Ed.

00:48:21.520 --> 00:48:22.728
Where did you put your money?

00:48:22.728 --> 00:48:24.790
Who's going to reach
the win-win outcomes--

00:48:24.790 --> 00:48:28.555
the newlyweds or the
previously unacquainted folks?

00:48:28.555 --> 00:48:29.770
AUDIENCE: No idea.

00:48:29.770 --> 00:48:31.450
LEIGH THOMPSON: No idea.

00:48:31.450 --> 00:48:33.160
Some of us-- yeah, oh, good.

00:48:33.160 --> 00:48:34.597
Caroline is going
to come through.

00:48:34.597 --> 00:48:36.888
AUDIENCE: I did this exercise
in the negotiation class,

00:48:36.888 --> 00:48:40.754
and it was a friend versus a
classmate that you don't know.

00:48:40.754 --> 00:48:42.795
And then when you
don't know, you always

00:48:42.795 --> 00:48:44.186
reach an agreement
with the kids.

00:48:44.186 --> 00:48:46.070
You're not afraid
to give and take.

00:48:46.070 --> 00:48:47.994
There's no repercussions
for the relationship.

00:48:47.994 --> 00:48:48.910
LEIGH THOMPSON: Right.

00:48:48.910 --> 00:48:52.780
So am I to think, Caroline,
that you would actually

00:48:52.780 --> 00:48:55.900
put your money on these people?

00:48:55.900 --> 00:48:58.330
Because the newlywed
couples are going

00:48:58.330 --> 00:49:00.190
to too quickly capitulate.

00:49:00.190 --> 00:49:02.474
They're not going
to have the chat

00:49:02.474 --> 00:49:03.640
that I was asking you about.

00:49:03.640 --> 00:49:05.015
They're going to
say, yes, honey,

00:49:05.015 --> 00:49:06.550
I think I can live with that.

00:49:06.550 --> 00:49:09.430
They're going to do
what Nobel laureate Herb

00:49:09.430 --> 00:49:10.570
Simon calls satisficing--

00:49:10.570 --> 00:49:11.980
I'm OK with that.

00:49:11.980 --> 00:49:13.340
It's fine with me.

00:49:13.340 --> 00:49:14.180
It's fine with me.

00:49:14.180 --> 00:49:15.550
So that's exactly what happened.

00:49:15.550 --> 00:49:17.650
The previously
unacquainted people

00:49:17.650 --> 00:49:22.540
were much more likely to reach
the win-win, elegant outcomes

00:49:22.540 --> 00:49:28.624
because the newlywed couples
took the low-hanging fruit.

00:49:28.624 --> 00:49:30.290
AUDIENCE: I think
that the results would

00:49:30.290 --> 00:49:32.090
differ if it was not newlywed.

00:49:32.090 --> 00:49:35.180
I think that the results
would differ if it was more--

00:49:35.180 --> 00:49:36.680
LEIGH THOMPSON:
Old, married people.

00:49:36.680 --> 00:49:38.625
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:49:38.625 --> 00:49:42.020
LEIGH THOMPSON: Old, married
people who are just saying--

00:49:42.020 --> 00:49:44.270
and that would be an
interesting study.

00:49:44.270 --> 00:49:46.310
I'm not sure that they
would reach the win-win.

00:49:46.310 --> 00:49:48.110
They might reach
the win or lose.

00:49:48.110 --> 00:49:50.180
But I think this is interesting.

00:49:50.180 --> 00:49:55.640
They deliberately use newlyweds,
because I want to keep it good.

00:49:55.640 --> 00:49:57.295
I want to agree with her.

00:49:57.295 --> 00:49:58.730
They're in the honeymoon stage.

00:49:58.730 --> 00:50:00.646
I think that that's where
the term comes from.

00:50:00.646 --> 00:50:02.220
We're in the honeymoon stage.

00:50:02.220 --> 00:50:04.070
So what I want to
do now is I want

00:50:04.070 --> 00:50:06.560
to get back to something that
I asked Boris and I asked

00:50:06.560 --> 00:50:07.580
all of you guys.

00:50:07.580 --> 00:50:11.210
So how do you create a team,
how do you create a culture

00:50:11.210 --> 00:50:13.340
where we can have a good chat?

00:50:13.340 --> 00:50:18.110
And so companies need to
establish what we call

00:50:18.110 --> 00:50:20.720
boxing rings and campfires.

00:50:20.720 --> 00:50:23.260
A boxing ring means
that we can have

00:50:23.260 --> 00:50:25.780
the tough conversations
and the debate,

00:50:25.780 --> 00:50:28.410
but it's not going
to get personal.

00:50:28.410 --> 00:50:34.740
We might even end up at the
common area, at the campfire.

00:50:34.740 --> 00:50:37.110
I actually-- when
I coach teams, I

00:50:37.110 --> 00:50:39.230
tell them disagree
about something

00:50:39.230 --> 00:50:40.530
in your first meeting.

00:50:40.530 --> 00:50:42.300
So I worked with
a team recently.

00:50:42.300 --> 00:50:47.737
And they decided-- you know
that show "Undercover Boss?"

00:50:47.737 --> 00:50:49.320
So we just picked
something innocuous.

00:50:49.320 --> 00:50:50.040
We just said, look.

00:50:50.040 --> 00:50:51.400
Everybody has heard
of "Undercover Boss."

00:50:51.400 --> 00:50:53.070
Do you think it's a
good show or a bad show?

00:50:53.070 --> 00:50:54.486
Some people think
it's a bad show.

00:50:54.486 --> 00:50:56.970
Some people said I
think it's a good show.

00:50:56.970 --> 00:51:00.260
Let's debate about something
that's not the big kahuna.

00:51:00.260 --> 00:51:03.277
Because when we have to
debate about the big kahuna,

00:51:03.277 --> 00:51:05.610
we can look back and say we've
already done this before.

00:51:05.610 --> 00:51:09.390
We've already had a
spirited discussion.

00:51:09.390 --> 00:51:12.960
Leaders practice debate
and have ground rules.

00:51:12.960 --> 00:51:15.099
So I have a woman in my class.

00:51:15.099 --> 00:51:16.890
She's actually in a
pharmaceutical company,

00:51:16.890 --> 00:51:17.956
not that that matters.

00:51:17.956 --> 00:51:20.580
She came up to me, and she said,
Leigh, I think I'm going nuts.

00:51:20.580 --> 00:51:21.871
I said, why are you going nuts?

00:51:21.871 --> 00:51:23.470
She goes, in my
previous company,

00:51:23.470 --> 00:51:26.409
the culture was very
much along the lines

00:51:26.409 --> 00:51:28.200
that Caroline and Boris
were talking about.

00:51:28.200 --> 00:51:30.120
People had spirited debate.

00:51:30.120 --> 00:51:31.500
They challenged one another.

00:51:31.500 --> 00:51:34.290
And for a variety of
reasons, in her new company,

00:51:34.290 --> 00:51:36.579
everybody was too polite.

00:51:36.579 --> 00:51:38.370
And I said, well, what
are you going to do?

00:51:38.370 --> 00:51:40.630
She goes, well, I've
hired a debate coach.

00:51:40.630 --> 00:51:44.340
Coach is going to
come in and teach us

00:51:44.340 --> 00:51:47.340
how to have a debate
that separates

00:51:47.340 --> 00:51:49.690
the people from the problem.

00:51:49.690 --> 00:51:53.410
So I want to now talk about
finding your inner negotiator.

00:51:53.410 --> 00:51:55.180
And I want to ask you guys--

00:51:55.180 --> 00:51:57.850
and this is not a trick
question or anything.

00:51:57.850 --> 00:52:02.457
What are the qualities of
an effective negotiator?

00:52:02.457 --> 00:52:03.790
And I'm not trying to trick you.

00:52:03.790 --> 00:52:06.180
Anything you say is going
to-- remind me of your name.

00:52:06.180 --> 00:52:06.470
AUDIENCE: Deborah.

00:52:06.470 --> 00:52:08.428
LEIGH THOMPSON: Deborah,
what are the qualities

00:52:08.428 --> 00:52:09.600
of an effective negotiator?

00:52:09.600 --> 00:52:10.030
AUDIENCE: Collaborative.

00:52:10.030 --> 00:52:11.472
LEIGH THOMPSON: Collaborative.

00:52:11.472 --> 00:52:12.263
AUDIENCE: Creative.

00:52:12.263 --> 00:52:13.960
LEIGH THOMPSON: Creative.

00:52:13.960 --> 00:52:15.802
Dimitri?

00:52:15.802 --> 00:52:16.670
AUDIENCE: Polite.

00:52:16.670 --> 00:52:17.545
LEIGH THOMPSON: What?

00:52:17.545 --> 00:52:18.392
AUDIENCE: Polite.

00:52:18.392 --> 00:52:19.350
LEIGH THOMPSON: Polite.

00:52:19.350 --> 00:52:21.640
Oh, I like that.

00:52:21.640 --> 00:52:23.064
Boris?

00:52:23.064 --> 00:52:27.600
AUDIENCE: I think the qualities
that [INAUDIBLE] goal and some

00:52:27.600 --> 00:52:28.600
[INAUDIBLE] negotiation.

00:52:28.600 --> 00:52:31.870
LEIGH THOMPSON: Goal focus,
that they're goal-focused.

00:52:31.870 --> 00:52:33.950
They have targets.

00:52:33.950 --> 00:52:36.761
Anything else, Dan?

00:52:36.761 --> 00:52:37.760
AUDIENCE: Good listener.

00:52:37.760 --> 00:52:38.650
LEIGH THOMPSON: Good listener.

00:52:38.650 --> 00:52:39.190
OK.

00:52:39.190 --> 00:52:43.660
So everything that you've said
is definitely on the list.

00:52:43.660 --> 00:52:46.000
And we actually
consulted with, I think,

00:52:46.000 --> 00:52:49.900
the world class negotiator,
Howard Raiffa of Harvard.

00:52:49.900 --> 00:52:53.630
And this is his
list that he used.

00:52:53.630 --> 00:52:55.050
And I'm kind of curious.

00:52:55.050 --> 00:52:57.250
Oh, she's used different
color fonts there.

00:52:57.250 --> 00:53:00.310
I can't imagine what he's doing.

00:53:00.310 --> 00:53:02.770
These are all qualities
that I think you mentioned

00:53:02.770 --> 00:53:05.110
or we would, in
spirit, agree with.

00:53:05.110 --> 00:53:07.000
Anything you notice
about this list?

00:53:07.000 --> 00:53:09.682
I'm just curious.

00:53:09.682 --> 00:53:11.140
Maybe I am trying
to trick you now.

00:53:11.140 --> 00:53:13.790
But not really.

00:53:13.790 --> 00:53:15.708
Dan, do you notice
anything about this list?

00:53:18.280 --> 00:53:20.500
For example, this
list versus this list?

00:53:24.960 --> 00:53:25.920
Nikki sees things.

00:53:25.920 --> 00:53:27.834
Alina sees things.

00:53:27.834 --> 00:53:29.720
AUDIENCE: I feel like
the one on the left

00:53:29.720 --> 00:53:34.440
is focused on what can I
get out of the negotiation.

00:53:34.440 --> 00:53:37.110
LEIGH THOMPSON: Yes,
self-interested.

00:53:37.110 --> 00:53:41.780
And the one on the
right would be--

00:53:41.780 --> 00:53:46.330
AUDIENCE: How do I basically
work with my [INAUDIBLE]?

00:53:46.330 --> 00:53:47.770
LEIGH THOMPSON: I think--

00:53:47.770 --> 00:53:50.620
yes, it's much more
outward focused.

00:53:50.620 --> 00:53:52.750
How can I be a win-win for you?

00:53:52.750 --> 00:53:57.250
So now I'm going to ask the
loaded, loaded question.

00:53:57.250 --> 00:54:03.910
Do you see any
gender issues here?

00:54:03.910 --> 00:54:04.419
Stereotypes?

00:54:04.419 --> 00:54:05.460
How about let's use that.

00:54:05.460 --> 00:54:07.210
Do we say any gender
stereotypes here?

00:54:07.210 --> 00:54:09.644
What do we see, Nikki?

00:54:09.644 --> 00:54:11.556
AUDIENCE: The guys
are [INAUDIBLE] women.

00:54:11.556 --> 00:54:12.520
LEIGH THOMPSON: Yes.

00:54:12.520 --> 00:54:13.110
OK.

00:54:13.110 --> 00:54:15.660
So what we did is
we took this list,

00:54:15.660 --> 00:54:18.780
and we asked people to do the
uncomfortable task that I just

00:54:18.780 --> 00:54:19.830
asked Nikki to do.

00:54:19.830 --> 00:54:23.700
We said, look, all
political correctness aside,

00:54:23.700 --> 00:54:26.970
just indicate which of these
are stereotypically male

00:54:26.970 --> 00:54:31.380
and stereotypically female,
using society's stereotypes,

00:54:31.380 --> 00:54:32.606
not yours.

00:54:32.606 --> 00:54:34.980
And the results were as crystal
clear as you can imagine.

00:54:34.980 --> 00:54:39.720
Most people said duh, these
sound like the stereotype

00:54:39.720 --> 00:54:42.680
of what it's like to be a guy--

00:54:42.680 --> 00:54:45.570
assertive, rational.

00:54:45.570 --> 00:54:47.400
I'm not going to get emotional.

00:54:47.400 --> 00:54:50.802
And the right-hand panel sounds
like stereotypical feminine,

00:54:50.802 --> 00:54:52.760
even though, obviously,
we don't agree with it.

00:54:52.760 --> 00:54:54.690
And you might be
saying I can't imagine

00:54:54.690 --> 00:54:56.970
what point you're making now.

00:54:56.970 --> 00:54:59.280
Well, then we did a study.

00:54:59.280 --> 00:55:03.750
And I want you to ignore the
right side and stay over here.

00:55:03.750 --> 00:55:09.970
So when we did a study,
we had very talented,

00:55:09.970 --> 00:55:16.140
motivated young managers,
people MBA-bound

00:55:16.140 --> 00:55:19.150
at very elite institutions,
do a negotiation

00:55:19.150 --> 00:55:20.340
that was fairly high stakes.

00:55:20.340 --> 00:55:24.330
I think it was a job simulation
that they took very seriously.

00:55:24.330 --> 00:55:29.280
And what we found is
that if you look up here,

00:55:29.280 --> 00:55:32.880
this should say
ambitiousness of targets.

00:55:32.880 --> 00:55:35.100
How high did they
set their North Star?

00:55:35.100 --> 00:55:37.820
What were they trying to
achieve in terms of a salary

00:55:37.820 --> 00:55:39.950
or starting options, et cetera?

00:55:39.950 --> 00:55:44.010
As you can see here, the
men set much higher goals

00:55:44.010 --> 00:55:45.910
than the women.

00:55:45.910 --> 00:55:48.540
This is men, this
is women, and this

00:55:48.540 --> 00:55:50.640
is how ambitious is my target.

00:55:50.640 --> 00:55:52.170
So the men set
much higher goals.

00:55:52.170 --> 00:55:54.540
And what I want to
emphasize is that this

00:55:54.540 --> 00:55:59.010
was a simulation where all
of the financial factors

00:55:59.010 --> 00:56:02.140
were the same for both people.

00:56:02.140 --> 00:56:05.350
Then what we did is we
did the exact same study.

00:56:05.350 --> 00:56:09.200
People had to do this high
stakes job simulation.

00:56:09.200 --> 00:56:11.380
But right before
they negotiated,

00:56:11.380 --> 00:56:15.670
everybody read a very
short page of information

00:56:15.670 --> 00:56:19.090
in which we took this column.

00:56:19.090 --> 00:56:22.930
We said just want you
to know that negotiation

00:56:22.930 --> 00:56:28.330
experts believe that
these qualities are

00:56:28.330 --> 00:56:30.130
important for being
a good negotiator.

00:56:30.130 --> 00:56:34.030
Otherwise, I keep repeating
everybody did the same dang

00:56:34.030 --> 00:56:34.780
thing.

00:56:34.780 --> 00:56:38.710
And what we found when we
used the positive female

00:56:38.710 --> 00:56:40.710
stereotype--

00:56:40.710 --> 00:56:44.970
all of a sudden, the women are
setting really high stretch

00:56:44.970 --> 00:56:46.510
goals.

00:56:46.510 --> 00:56:50.560
The financial factors in the
negotiation did not change.

00:56:50.560 --> 00:56:52.840
But somehow, when
we, in some sense,

00:56:52.840 --> 00:56:56.230
affirmed the female
stereotype-- again,

00:56:56.230 --> 00:56:58.940
it was a stereotype--
the women did better.

00:56:58.940 --> 00:57:03.250
Now, you might be
saying, goals, schmoals.

00:57:03.250 --> 00:57:06.790
What happened in their
employment packages?

00:57:06.790 --> 00:57:09.340
Well, as you can see here--

00:57:09.340 --> 00:57:10.720
ignore this junk.

00:57:10.720 --> 00:57:14.220
In the control condition, the
way to read these weird data

00:57:14.220 --> 00:57:19.540
is that the higher the bar,
the higher the northbound bar,

00:57:19.540 --> 00:57:22.090
men did better than
women, because we actually

00:57:22.090 --> 00:57:25.970
had them negotiating across
the table with each other.

00:57:25.970 --> 00:57:31.220
When they had read about the
positive female stereotype,

00:57:31.220 --> 00:57:33.510
the women actually did better.

00:57:33.510 --> 00:57:38.360
So our take away
message is something

00:57:38.360 --> 00:57:41.750
as subtle as
reminding people what

00:57:41.750 --> 00:57:44.570
are the qualities
of a good negotiator

00:57:44.570 --> 00:57:48.260
can have a dramatic
impact on setting goals

00:57:48.260 --> 00:57:51.860
and actually how I choose
to use the information

00:57:51.860 --> 00:57:53.760
in the situation.

00:57:53.760 --> 00:57:56.180
And I close with another study.

00:57:56.180 --> 00:57:58.460
This is the one that's
kind of over the top here.

00:57:58.460 --> 00:58:01.040
This is what we call
the gorilla effect.

00:58:01.040 --> 00:58:03.380
And I'm trying to show a
gorilla in the background here

00:58:03.380 --> 00:58:04.700
that's not coming through.

00:58:04.700 --> 00:58:05.690
We had a control group.

00:58:05.690 --> 00:58:07.040
We just said do a negotiation.

00:58:07.040 --> 00:58:07.760
It's high stakes.

00:58:07.760 --> 00:58:08.260
Good luck.

00:58:08.260 --> 00:58:09.500
It's going to mean a lot.

00:58:09.500 --> 00:58:11.340
We had a unisex group.

00:58:11.340 --> 00:58:13.040
In other words,
we said, actually,

00:58:13.040 --> 00:58:17.750
negotiation, Dan, really
involves good judgment, sense

00:58:17.750 --> 00:58:20.580
of humor, patient and prepared.

00:58:20.580 --> 00:58:24.230
In other words, that
sounds like everybody.

00:58:24.230 --> 00:58:26.170
And then we had a gorilla group.

00:58:26.170 --> 00:58:30.110
And in the gorilla
group, we said, well,

00:58:30.110 --> 00:58:33.380
there are sex differences
in negotiation.

00:58:33.380 --> 00:58:37.100
And what we found, in
some sense, surprised us.

00:58:37.100 --> 00:58:43.570
We found that the women did
the best in the gorilla group.

00:58:43.570 --> 00:58:49.050
In other words, the higher
bars indicate that women

00:58:49.050 --> 00:58:50.760
performed better than men.

00:58:50.760 --> 00:58:53.070
And I'm curious-- do you guys
have hypotheses about why

00:58:53.070 --> 00:58:54.380
that might be the case?

00:59:00.020 --> 00:59:02.270
AUDIENCE: Because you're
so accustomed to proving

00:59:02.270 --> 00:59:04.084
stereotypes wrong.

00:59:04.084 --> 00:59:05.250
LEIGH THOMPSON: That's good.

00:59:05.250 --> 00:59:06.176
Say it again.

00:59:06.176 --> 00:59:08.310
AUDIENCE: If we're accustomed
to trying to prove stereotypes.

00:59:08.310 --> 00:59:10.226
LEIGH THOMPSON: I think
that that's brilliant.

00:59:10.226 --> 00:59:14.510
So in other words, you
give me some stereotype,

00:59:14.510 --> 00:59:17.930
guess who's going to show you
that that's dead wrong right

00:59:17.930 --> 00:59:18.530
now.

00:59:18.530 --> 00:59:22.850
So in other words, when we
gave women the tip off that,

00:59:22.850 --> 00:59:25.520
you know what, there
are gender differences,

00:59:25.520 --> 00:59:28.490
their response was not today.

00:59:28.490 --> 00:59:31.349
So we think that that's
kind of interesting.

00:59:31.349 --> 00:59:33.140
And so one of the things
that we're doing--

00:59:33.140 --> 00:59:35.598
and I'm going to try to close
very soon-- one of the things

00:59:35.598 --> 00:59:37.595
that we're doing in our
research with gender

00:59:37.595 --> 00:59:40.070
at the negotiation
table is we're

00:59:40.070 --> 00:59:45.000
looking at holding constant
the financial information,

00:59:45.000 --> 00:59:48.830
it's really about how am I
going to use that information,

00:59:48.830 --> 00:59:51.530
and what are the expectations
I have of myself.

00:59:51.530 --> 00:59:55.190
So to come full circle
here, we talk in the book

00:59:55.190 --> 00:59:56.450
about a lot of these traps.

00:59:56.450 --> 00:59:58.430
And again, the whole
idea is that a lot

00:59:58.430 --> 01:00:01.180
of what we're doing
in our companies--

01:00:01.180 --> 01:00:04.630
90% of what we're
doing is probably

01:00:04.630 --> 01:00:05.830
working toward great ends.

01:00:05.830 --> 01:00:09.130
But sometimes, when
we take some of these,

01:00:09.130 --> 01:00:11.290
it can work against us.

